le = PSL Grand Prix Champions |\n years = [[2014 PSL Grand Prix Conference|2014]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n before = [[Philippine Army Lady Troopers|Generika-Army Lady Troopers]] |\n after = [[F2 Logistics Cargo Movers]] |\n title = PSL All-Filipino Champions |\n years = [[2015 PSL All-Filipino Conference|2015]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n before = [[RC Cola Raiders|RC Cola-Army \"A\"]] |\n after = [[Petron Blaze Spikers|Petron]]  |\n title = PSL Beach Volleyball Challenge Cup Champions |\n years = [[2017 PSL Beach Volleyball Challenge Cup|2017]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n before = [[F2 Logistics Cargo Movers|F2 Logistics]] |\n after = [[Petron Blaze Spikers|Petron]] |\n title = PSL All-Filipino Champions |\n years = [[2017 PSL All-Filipino Conference|2017]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n before = [[F2 Logistics Cargo Movers|F2 Logistics]] |\n after = [[Petron Blaze Spikers|Petron]] |\n title = PSL Grand Prix Champions |\n years = [[2018 PSL Grand Prix Conference|2018]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n before = [[Petron Blaze Spikers|Petron]] |\n after = (incumbent) |\n title = PSL Grand Prix Champions |\n years = [[2019 PSL Grand Prix Conference|2019]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Petron Blaze Spikers}}\n{{2015 All-Filipino Petron Champions Team}}\n{{2014 Grand Prix Petron Champions Team}}\n{{Philippine Super Liga}}\n\n[[Category:Volleyball clubs in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine Super Liga]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Volleyball clubs established in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKatherine Bell(link changed toKatherine Bell (volleyball)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petron_Tri-Activ_Spikers"}
{"title_page": "Tesla Factory", "text_new": "{{short description|Automobile manufacturing plant in south Fremont, California}}\n{{about|the Tesla factory in Fremont, CA, USA|the factory in Nevada|Gigafactory 1|the factory in Buffalo, NY|Gigafactory 2|the factory in Shanghai, China|Giga Shanghai|the factory in Tilburg, Netherlands|Tesla facilities in Tilburg|the planned factory in Berlin, Germany|Gigafactory 4}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox factory\n|name=Tesla Factory\n|image=File:Tesla_auto_bots.jpg\n|caption=[[Tesla Model S]] assembly at the Tesla Factory\n|location=[[Fremont, California]]\n|industry=[[Automotive industry]]\n|products=[[Tesla Model S]]<br>[[Tesla Model X]]<br>\n[[Tesla Model 3]]\n|employees=10,000\n|built={{start date|1962}} as [[Fremont Assembly]]<br>{{start date|2010}} as Tesla Factory\n|address=45000 Fremont Boulevard<br>[[Fremont, California]]  94538\n|owner=[[Tesla, Inc.]]|coordinates={{coord|37|29|41.12|N|121|56|41.16|W}}}}\n\nThe '''Tesla Factory''' is an [[automobile]] [[manufacturing]] [[factory|plant]] in [[Fremont, California]], operated by [[Tesla, Inc.]] The facility opened as the [[General Motors]] [[Fremont Assembly]] in 1962, and was later operated by [[NUMMI]], a former [[General Motors|GM]]\u2013[[Toyota]] joint venture.<ref name=\"sjbj\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2010/10/27/tesla-officially-replaces-nummi.html |first=Lisa |last=Sibley |title=Tesla officially replaces NUMMI in Fremont |date=2010-10-27}}</ref> Tesla took ownership in 2010.<ref name=\"tesla factory release\" /> The plant {{As of|2019|May|df=|alt=currently}} manufactures the [[Tesla Model S|Model S]], [[Tesla Model X|Model X]], and [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]], employing 10,000 people {{As of|2018|June|df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"SJ Merc June 2018 racism lawsuit\" />\n\n==Background==\nTesla had planned for an assembly factory in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], as a central location for shipping.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teslamotors.com/media/press_room.php?id=257 |title=Tesla Motors press release - announcement of Albuquerque plant |publisher=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406182037/http://www.teslamotors.com/media/press_room.php?id=257 |archivedate=2010-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Severns |first=Dave |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog1/?p=52 |title=Tesla Motors blog post regarding Albuquerque decision |publisher=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317081628/http://www.teslamotors.com/blog1/?p=52 |archivedate=2007-03-17}}</ref> Construction was supposed to begin in April 2007, but was canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2007/aug/21/editorial-dont-hold-your-breath-tesla-motors-plant/ |title=The Albuquerque Tribune Editorial: Don't hold your breath on Tesla Motors plant |publisher=Abqtrib.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214022134/http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2007/aug/21/editorial-dont-hold-your-breath-tesla-motors-plant/ |archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref> A separate [[greenfield project|greenfield]] factory to be built in [[San Jose, California]] was also announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_9745521 |title=Tesla to build electric car factory in Bay Area - San Jose Mercury News |publisher=Mercurynews.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120920174832/http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_9745521 |archivedate=2012-09-20}}</ref> However, the cost was prohibitive, and the company looked for alternatives. Tesla initially also dismissed NUMMI for being too big and costly.<ref name=odell/>\n\nSome of the current facility was operated as the GM [[Fremont Assembly]] from 1962 to 1982, and between 1984 and 2009 was used by New United Motor Manufacturing, Inc. ([[NUMMI]]),<ref name=aw2017-03/> a joint venture between [[General Motors]] and [[Toyota]],<ref name=\"sjbj\"/><ref name=\"How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED)\">{{cite web |title=How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TEReFPI4jSc |website=YouTube|publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> producing 357,809 cars and trucks in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://autointell.com/nao_companies/general_motors/gm-manufacturing/gm-nummi/gmnummi.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160314051152/http://autointell.com/nao_companies/general_motors/gm-manufacturing/gm-nummi/gmnummi.htm |title=GM Nummi Plant|archivedate=2016-03-14|accessdate=2016-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> Proposals to continue the site after 2010 included [[Aurica Motors|Aurica EVs]], state incentives to Toyota, and a stadium, but [[NUMMI#Alternatives to closure|none of them succeeded]]. In 2010 the mayor of Fremont viewed the site as dead.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nThe plant is located in the [[Fremont, California#South Fremont District|South Fremont District]] between the [[Warm Springs / South Fremont (BART station)|Warm Springs BART station]]<ref name=warmsprings>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2016/06/15/toll-brothers-buys-big-fremont-site-near-bart.html |title=Toll Brothers buys land near Fremont Warm Springs BART station |first=Nathan |last=Donato-Weinstein |work=Silicon Valley Business Journal |location=US |date=2016-06-15 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> and the [[California State Route 262]] connecting I880 and I680. [[Union Pacific Railroad]] has tracks at the plant<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vta.org/bart/missionwarren |title=Mission/Warren Area Improvements |publisher=Santa Clara Valley Transportation Authority |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2013/07/19/tesla-buys-big-chunk-of-fremont-land.html |title=Tesla Motors buys test track in 35-acre deal |first=Nathan |last=Donato-Weinstein |work=Silicon Valley Business Journal |location=US |date=2013-07-19 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> which carry finished cars.<ref name=2015ecP8>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/8/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010027/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/8/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=8 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref> [[Rail freight transport]] is also used to receive batteries and Model 3 drivetrains from Tesla's [[Gigafactory 1]]<!-- and other parts-->.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nevada/tesla-officials-show-progress-gigafactory-northern-nevada|title=Tesla officials show off progress at Gigafactory in Northern Nevada|first=SEAN WHALEY LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL CAPITAL |last=BUREAU|date=2016-03-18 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160803161348/http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nevada/tesla-officials-show-progress-gigafactory-northern-nevada |archivedate=2016-08-03 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2010, [[Tesla Inc.]] and Toyota announced a partnership to work on electric vehicle development and collaborate on the \"development of electric vehicles, parts, and production system and engineering support\". This included Tesla's partial purchase of the former NUMMI site, mainly consisting of the factory building,<ref name=\"sfbiz\">{{cite news |author=Lindsay Riddell |title=Tesla to buy NUMMI plant, build cars with Toyota |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2010/05/17/daily65.html |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=2010-04-20 |accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref><ref name=\"kvtu\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/23625639/detail.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523055832/http://www.ktvu.com/news/23625639/detail.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-05-23 |title=Tesla Wants NUMMI Operational By 2012 |work=KVTU.com |date=2010-05-21 |accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> for $42 million.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/05/27/BUL21DLN2C.DTL |title=Tesla paid only $42 million for Nummi plant |first=David R. |last=Baker |newspaper=[[San Francisco Gate]] |date=2010-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\"detnews\">{{cite news |last=Tierney |first=Christine |url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20100520/AUTO01/5200516/1148/Toyota-invests-in-Tesla-to-help-reopen-Calif.-plant |title=Toyota invests in Tesla to help reopen Calif. plant |newspaper=The Detroit News |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-05-22}}{{Dead link|date=April 2012}}</ref>\n\nTesla officially took possession of the site on October 19, 2010,<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news |author=PUI-WING TAM |title=Idle Fremont Plant Gears Up for Tesla |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704300604575554662948527140 |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2011-04-03 |quote=Parts of the Fremont facility will be mothballed since Tesla is only using a fraction of the space. \"When Nummi said it would close, the land was dead,\" says Fremont Mayor Bob Wasserman. When Tesla announced its Nummi deal in May, he says, \"the land became alive\" again |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150316123930/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704300604575554662948527140 |url-status=live |archive-date=2015-03-16 }}</ref> and opened it on October 27.<ref name=\"tesla factory release\">{{cite press_release | url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/releasedetail.cfm?releaseid=523911 | title=Tesla Motors Opens Tesla Factory - Home of the Model S | publisher=Tesla Motors | date=2010-10-27 | accessdate=2012-07-18}}</ref> The state of California has supported the renewal, expecting tax income from sustained jobs.<ref name=taxrebate1>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/la-fi-hy-musk-subsidies-box-20150530-story.html |title=Three companies, $4.9 billion in government support |author=Jerry Hirsch |date=2015-05-30 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2015-10-29 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151025213157/http://www.latimes.com/local/la-fi-hy-musk-subsidies-box-20150530-story.html |archivedate=2015-10-25 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=rtRebate>{{cite web |url=https://www.rt.com/usa/264065-musk-tesla-government-subsidies/ |title=Musk defends receiving $4.9 billion in government support for Tesla, SolarCity and SpaceX |work=RT English |accessdate=2015-10-29 }}</ref><ref>http://www.business.ca.gov/Portals/0/CA%20Competes/Docs/Agreements/FY1415P3Large/Tesla%20Motors,%20Inc.%20-%20CCTC%20Agreement.pdf</ref> The first retail delivery of the Tesla Model S took place during a special event at the Tesla Factory on June 22, 2012.<ref name=1stDelivery>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_20919722/silicon-valley-milestone-tesla-motors-begins-delivering-model?refresh=no |title=In a Silicon Valley milestone, Tesla Motors begins delivering Model S electric cars |author=John Boudreau |work=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2012-06-22}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Wide image|NUMMIplantMissionPeakPanorama 3199.jpg|800px|The former NUMMI (now Tesla) plant in Fremont, California}}\n\n==Facilities==\nNUMMI auctioned off<ref name=Maynards>{{cite web|url=http://www.equipmentappraisalsandauctions.com/new-united-motor-manufacturing.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613192846/http://www.equipmentappraisalsandauctions.com/new-united-motor-manufacturing.html |title=New United Motor Manufacturing Appraisals|work=Maynards |archivedate=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> the press lines, robots and other equipment to [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Kentucky|Toyota's]] [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Texas|other US]] [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Mississippi|factories]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20110918/OEM01/309189998/toyota-gave-old-robots-new-tools-to-trim-u.s.-camry-price-2 |title=Toyota gave old robots new tools to trim U.S. Camry price 2% |date=2011-09-18 |first=Alan |last=Ohnsman |work=[[Automotive News]] |accessdate=2017-06-05 |quote=Along with the production robots transferred to Toyota's Georgetown, Ky., plant that makes most of the Camrys sold in North America, Nummi equipment was also acquired by Toyota's San Antonio plant and electric-car maker Tesla Motors Inc.}}</ref><ref name=Hull2010>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/09/16/2010-tesla-gets-ready-to-take-over-the-former-nummi-auto-plant-in-fremont/ |title=2010: Tesla gets ready to take over the former NUMMI auto plant in Fremont |first=Dana |last=Hull |newspaper=The Mercury News |date=2010-09-16 |accessdate=2017-06-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502023843/http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/09/16/2010-tesla-gets-ready-to-take-over-the-former-nummi-auto-plant-in-fremont/ |archivedate=2017-05-02 |url-status=live |quote=The entire NUMMI facility covers about 370 acres. Tesla is buying 210 acres, a parcel that contains several buildings that have approximately 4.7 million square feet of floor space. NUMMI\u2019s existing press line will be taken apart and sent to Toyota\u2019s plant in Blue Springs, Miss.}}</ref> and Tesla purchased over $17 million of manufacturing equipment and spare parts in 2011, at significant discounts compared to new equipment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/11009706/1/tesla-motors-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2010-results.html |title=Tesla Motors Reports Fourth Quarter And Full Year 2010 Results |work=[[TheStreet]] |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2014-09-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727000648/https://www.thestreet.com/story/11009706/1/tesla-motors-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2010-results.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Additionally, Tesla bought a Schuler SMG hydraulic stamping press, worth $50 million, for $6 million, including shipping costs from Detroit.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/>\n\nThe factory was about 10 times the size Tesla initially needed,<ref name=odell>{{cite news |last=O'Dell |first=John |url=https://www.edmunds.com/autoobserver-archive/2010/03/would-be-ev-makers-plan-to-save-nummi-auto-plant-a-long-shot-at-best.html |title=Would-Be EV Maker's 'Plan' to Save NUMMI Auto Plant a Long Shot at Best |publisher=Green Car Advisor |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2010-04-02| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315144830/http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/03/would-be-ev-makers-plan-to-save-nummi-auto-plant-a-long-shot-at-best.html| archivedate=2010-03-15 | url-status=live |quote=Tesla had been wooed as a NUMMI tenant by politicians and economic development people .. But Tesla - which has all of about 550 employees and plans to ramp up to around 2,000 when it starts building its next vehicle in 2012, the Model S electric sedan - took a look at the costs involved and rejected the idea out of hand. The plant, said Straubel, is about 10 times the size of a facility Tesla would need to build even 20,000 cars a year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Inside Out \u2014 Tesla History From 7-Year Insider |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/11/09/tesla-inside-out-tesla-history-from-7-year-insider/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=9 November 2019 |quote=2012, he noted how empty and \u201cpost-apocalyptic\u201d the Fremont factory seemed. Tesla was only using about 10% of the space}}</ref><ref name=loveday2014/> and much of the {{convert|370|acre|sqft m2|adj=on}} site was unused in 2013, with most activity concentrated in the {{convert|5500000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} main building that does the final assembly of vehicles.<ref name=\"WSJ\" />\n\nVarious parts of the NUMMI plant were planned to be modified to support Tesla vehicle production. For example, the passenger vehicle paint equipment was to be extensively modified through late 2011;<ref name=\"WSJ\" />{{update after|2013|7|25}} converted from solvents to [[BASF]] water-based paint.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/> Two [[Electrostatic coating|paint lines]] (one car body, one component) were constructed from 2015.<!--capacity unclear--><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.eisenmann.com/en/media/press/press-releases/2015/2015_03_31_Tesla_Motors.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160405235244/http://www.eisenmann.com/en/media/press/press-releases/2015/2015_03_31_Tesla_Motors.html |title=Tesla Motors building the world\u2019s most advanced paint shop \u2013 with Eisenmann technology|date=2015-03-31 |archivedate=2016-04-05|publisher=Eisenmann |accessdate=2016-10-13 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |title=Tesla Motors Model 3 Equipment \"Already Online\" at Fremont Factory|work=The Country Caller|date=2016-08-04|accessdate=2016-10-13|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161013221553/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |archive-date=October 13, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3s-incorporated.com/projects/project/tesla-motors-paint-shop |title=Paint Shop Detection and Suppression Systems - 3S Incorporated|publisher= |accessdate=2016-10-13 }}</ref> By 2014, half of the factory area was in use.<ref name=loveday2014>{{cite web |last1=Loveday |first1=Eric |title=Tesla Motors Fremont Factory Usage Now Almost At 50% |url=https://insideevs.com/news/321993/tesla-motors-fremont-factory-usage-now-almost-at-50/ |website=InsideEVs |language=en |date=2014-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe floors, walls and ceiling are painted white with skylights and high-efficiency lighting to create an environment similar to a laboratory,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Factory |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/factory |website=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2015-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.natgeotv.com/ca/megafactories/videos/brand-new-tesla-factory |title=Brand New Tesla Factory|work=National Geographic |date=2012 |accessdate=2017-06-15 <!-- mirror https://www.tesla.com/videos/national-geographic-megafactories-trailer -->}}</ref> and the production environment is cleaner and quieter than at NUMMI.<ref name=aw2017-03>{{cite magazine |url=http://autoweek.com/article/tesla/where-el-caminos-and-vibes-were-born-new-teslas-are-built-california |title=We visit the Tesla Factory, formerly Fremont Assembly and NUMMI |first=Murilee |last=Martin |magazine=[[Autoweek]] |date=2017-03-08 |accessdate=2017-04-08 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170329211120/http://autoweek.com/article/tesla/where-el-caminos-and-vibes-were-born-new-teslas-are-built-california |archive-date=2017-03-29 |url-status=live |quote=I spent a fair amount of time at NUMMI, and it seemed like a rackety, chaotic place on the production line .. Fast-forward 28 years, and the same facility is a brightly-lit, no-earplugs-needed, high-tech operation}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Tesla acquired an adjacent 35-acre property from Union Pacific Railroad for a test track.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Avalos|first1=George |title=Tesla buys land for test track in Fremont|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2013/07/19/tesla-buys-land-for-test-track-in-fremont/ |website=The Mercury News|accessdate=2018-02-17|date=2013-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=Jay|title=Picture (s) Of The Day: Tesla's Test Track In Fremont In Action|url= https://insideevs.com/picture-s-day-teslas-test-track-fremont-action/ |website=insideevs.com|accessdate=2018-02-17}}</ref>\n\nTesla built a casting foundry in [[Lathrop, California|Lathrop]] in 2015 supporting the Fremont production,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Acquires 431,000 Square Foot Facility In Lathrop, California - Begins \"Manufacturing Modifications\" Of Site |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-acquires-431000-square-foot-facility-lathrop-california-begins-manufacturing-modifications-site/ |last1=Loveday |first1=Eric |website=InsideEVs |date=2014-04-22 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EGHsDqwSY28 |title=Elon Musk is ecstatic about Powerwall demand - Tesla Q1 2015 Earnings call (2015) AUDIO}} at 1h02m</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/12/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150511004338/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/12/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=12 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/3151236-tesla-motors-tsla-elon-reeve-musk-on-q1-2015-results-earnings-call-transcript |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Elon Reeve Musk on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript |work=Seeking Alpha |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> and leased 1.3 million sq ft of warehouses in nearby [[Livermore, California|Livermore]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2017/03/23/real-deals-industrial-tesla-at-oaks-logistics.html |title=Tesla seals the deal on East Bay's largest industrial lease ever |last=Lucas |first=Scott |date=2017-03-24 |access-date=2017-06-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170613160747/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2017/03/23/real-deals-industrial-tesla-at-oaks-logistics.html |archive-date=2017-06-13 |url-status=live |quote=It leased 1.3 million square feet spread across three buildings}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, there were 4,500 parking spaces,<ref name=FremontMasterPlan/> and Tesla purchased a neighboring 25-acre site<ref name=sfc2016-10-07/> from housing developer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/print-edition/2016/04/29/warm-springs-district-fremont-lennar-homes-office.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161013105227/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/print-edition/2016/04/29/warm-springs-district-fremont-lennar-homes-office.html |title=Lennar plans huge R&D, housing complex at Warm Springs 'innovation district' near Tesla plant in Fremont |date=2016-04-29|archivedate=2016-10-13 |work=San Francisco Business Times|accessdate=2016-10-13 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lennar Corporation|Lennar]]. Tesla announced in August 2017 it won approval from the Fremont City Council to double the size of the facility with about 4.6 million new square feet of space.<ref name=\"eastbaytimes.com\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/08/10/tesla-factory-launches-expansion-that-could-double-its-size/ |title=Tesla factory launches expansion that could double its size|date=2017-08-11|website=East Bay Times|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> Tesla also planned to expand production capacity five-fold to 500,000 vehicles per year by 2018,<ref name=\"eastbaytimes.com\"/> or 10,000 units per week.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.thedrive.com/sheetmetal/13594/tesla-continues-growth-to-double-its-fremont-plant-in-size |title=Tesla Continues Growth to Double its Fremont Plant in Size|last=Stumpf|first=Rob |work=The Drive|access-date=2017-08-21 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Employees==\nTesla started production with 1,000 workers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Tesla-starts-delivery-out-of-former-Nummi-plant-3653530.php |title=Tesla starts delivery out of former Nummi plant |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=David R. |last=Baker |date=2012-06-22}}</ref> By 2013, this had risen to 3,000,<ref>{{cite web |title=Peek Inside Tesla\u2019s Robotic Factory |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/07/tesla-plant-video/ |website=Wired |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2013-07-16}}</ref> and to 6,000 people in June 2016.<ref name=employees>{{cite news |url=http://www.thecountrycaller.com/40182-tesla-motors-tsla-workers-being-contacted-by-uaw-for-union-formation/ |title=Tesla Motors Inc Workers Being Contacted by UAW For Union Formation |first=Angela |last=Campbell |work=The Country Caller |location=US |date=2016-06-09 |access-date=2016-07-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716082915/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/40182-tesla-motors-tsla-workers-being-contacted-by-uaw-for-union-formation/ |archivedate=2016-07-16}}</ref> In 2016, preparing for Model 3 production, Tesla planned to increase their work force to about 9,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconvalley.com/2016/12/08/fremont-city-council-approves-major-tesla-facility-expansion-plan/ |title=Fremont: City Council approves major Tesla facility expansion plan |first=Joseph |last=Geha |work=Silicon Valley |date=2016-12-08 |accessdate=2016-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fremontca.viebit.com/player.php?hash=agZlS6YYsCie |title=Video: Planning Commission Meeting, December 6, 2016. Time 1:40:20 and 2:16 |publisher=|date=2016-12-06 |accessdate=2017-01-17 }}</ref><ref name=FremontMasterPlan>[http://www.sfchronicle.com/file/178/7/1787-_16-0830%20Tesla%20Master%20Plan%20Final%20copy.pdf Master plan Tesla, Warm Springs. Summer 2016] [https://web.archive.org/web/20161008144132/http://www.sfchronicle.com/file/178/7/1787-_16-0830%20Tesla%20Master%20Plan%20Final%20copy.pdf Archive]</ref><ref name=sfc2016-10-07>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/New-Tesla-plan-could-double-size-of-Fremont-9936003.php |title=Tesla\u2019s new long-range plan could double size of Fremont factory|date=2016-10-07|work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2016/10/07/a-gigafactory-california-style-tesla-seeks-to-double-size-of-us-auto-plant/ |title=A Gigafactory, California Style? Tesla Seeks To Double Size of US Auto Plant|date=2016-10-07 |work=Forbes|accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fremontcityca.iqm2.com/Citizens/FileOpen.aspx?Type=1&ID=1338&Inline=True |title=Fremont Planning Commission Agenda |last=|first=|date=2016-10-13 |website=|publisher=Fremont Planning Commission |access-date=2017-01-17 |quote=File size=64 MB }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fremontca.viebit.com/player.php?hash=IKJWDr1IEupJ |title=Video: Planning Commission Meeting, October 27, 2016. Time 10:40 to 58:40|publisher=|date=2016-10-27 |accessdate=2017-01-17 }}</ref> In fall of 2017, Tesla employed some 10,000 at the Fremont plant,<ref name=\"SJ Merc Oct. 2017 hundreds fired after performance reviews\">{{cite web |last1=Hansen |first1=Louis |title=Tesla fires hundreds after company-wide performance reviews |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/10/13/4819750/ |website=The Mercury News |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2017-10-13}}</ref> a number still being shared in June 2018.<ref name=\"SJ Merc June 2018 racism lawsuit\">{{cite web |last1=Baron |first1=Ethan |title=Tesla fails in bid to push racism lawsuit into arbitration |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/06/04/tesla-fails-in-bid-to-push-racism-lawsuit-into-arbitration/ |website=The Mercury News |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Tesla employees, the company uses contractors for various functions. In May 2018, Elon Musk, in an apparent goal of reducing dead weight and raising efficiency and quality within its operation, decided to cut contractors and sub-contractors, ordering staff to justify and personally vouch for contractors worth keeping.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dellinger |first1=AJ |title=Tesla Will Lock Out Contractors on Monday Unless Employees Vouch For Them |url=https://gizmodo.com/tesla-will-lock-out-contractors-on-monday-unless-employ-1825812405 |website=Gizmodo |accessdate=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Elektrek May 2018 contractor justification\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla starts brutal review of contractors, firing everyone that is not vouched for by an employee |url=https://electrek.co/2018/05/06/tesla-brutal-review-contractors-firing-vouching-employee/ |website=Electrek |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2018-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:New Teslas at the factory.jpg|thumb|New [[Tesla Model S]] cars at the Tesla Factory in 2012]]\n\nThe plant's first [[series production]] vehicle is the [[Tesla Model S]] full-sized [[Battery electric vehicle|battery electric]] [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]].\n\nIn 2011, Tesla transitioned from 20 hand-assembled \"alpha builds\" to 50 \"beta builds\",<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gigaom.com/2011/03/17/photos-inside-teslas-model-s-alpha-workshop/ |title=PHOTOS: Inside Tesla\u2019s Model S Alpha Workshop|date=2011-03-17 |work=gigaom.com |accessdate=2017-06-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151204205900/https://gigaom.com/2011/03/17/photos-inside-teslas-model-s-alpha-workshop/ |archive-date=2015-12-04 |url-status= live }}</ref> production-validation vehicles built entirely at the Tesla Factory. These cars would also be used for system integration, engineering testing, and federal crash-testing and certification.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/autopia/2011/01/tesla-wants-some-engineering-cred |title=Tesla Wants Some Engineering Cred |first=Chuck |last=Squatriglia |work=[[Wired.com]] |date=2011-01-06}}</ref> Tesla expected to produce about 5,000 Model S sedans in 2012, with production ramping up to 20,000 in 2013 if necessary.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Ohnsman |title=Tesla Model S Assembly to Begin With Highest-Priced Version |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/tesla-says-model-s-production-to-begin-with-highest-priced-model.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110311153747/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/tesla-says-model-s-production-to-begin-with-highest-priced-model.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-03-11 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=2010-03-07 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://europe.autonews.com/article/20170102/ANE/161219895 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170109132511/http://europe.autonews.com/article/20170102/ANE/161219895 |title=Tesla Model S assembly to begin with highest-priced version |date=2011-03-07 |archivedate=2017-01-09 |newspaper=Automotive News|accessdate=2017-01-09 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first retail delivery of the Model S took place during a special event held at the Tesla Factory on June 22, 2012.<ref name=1stDelivery/> Production grew from 15\u201320 cars completed/week in August 2012<ref name=\"InsideTesla\">{{cite web |last=Blankenship |first=George |title=Inside Tesla |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/inside-tesla-082112 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2012-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> to over 200 by November 5<ref>{{cite web |last=Tesla Motors |title=Tesla Motors, Inc. \u2013 Third Quarter 2012 Shareholder Letter |url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1193125-12-450383&CIK=1318605 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2012-11-05 |accessdate=2012-12-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160502145601/http://ir.teslamotors.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1193125-12-450383&CIK=1318605 |archive-date=May 2, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and 400 by late December.<ref name=Sales2012>{{cite web |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2013/02/20/tesla-delivered-2-650-model-s-evs-last-year-musk-confident-of-p/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160417062435/http://www.autoblog.com/2013/02/20/tesla-delivered-2-650-model-s-evs-last-year-musk-confident-of-p/ |archive-date=2016-04-17 |title=Tesla delivered 2,650 Model S EVs last year, Musk confident of profit in Q1 and beyond |author=Domenick Yoney |publisher=Autoblog |date=2013-02-20 |accessdate=2013-03-10}} Around 2,650 Model S cars were delivered in the U.S. during 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.treehugger.com/cars/teslas-factory-reaches-20000-model-s-year-run-rate.html |title=Tesla Reaches 20,000 Unit Production Rate Annually for Model S |author=Michael Graham Richard |work=treehugger.com |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref> In late December Tesla revised their 2012 delivery projections down to 2,500 cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Make Way for Kilowatts: A Growing-Up Year for Plug-Ins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/23/automobiles/a-growing-up-year-for-plug-ins.html?_r=0 |work=New York Times |accessdate=2012-12-24 |date=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n\nDeliveries reached 6,892 units in the last three months of 2013.<ref name=Tesla4Q2013>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-02-19/teslas-stock-remains-electric-on-higher-sales-forecast |title=Tesla's Stock Remains Electric on Higher Sales Forecast |author=Ashlee Vance |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |date=2014-02-19 |accessdate=2014-02-19}}</ref> In December 2013, California announced it would give Tesla a US$34.7 million tax break to expand production by an estimated 35,000 vehicles annually from its Fremont, California plant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1089205_tesla-to-add-production-capacity-for-35000-more-electric-cars |title=Tesla To Add Production Capacity For 35,000 More Electric Cars |author=Antony Ingram |work=greencarreports.com |date=2013-12-18 |accessdate=2013-12-18}}</ref>\n\nTesla announced that production was expected to climb from 600 cars per week in early 2014 to about 1,000 units per week by year-end.<ref name=Tesla2013Sales>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hy-fourth-quarter-loss-telsa-20140219,0,6840087,full.story |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160124104551/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hy-fourth-quarter-loss-telsa-20140219-story.html |archive-date=2016-01-24 |title=Tesla Motors ends year with higher sales but still a big loss |author=Jerry Hirsch |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2014-02-19 |accessdate=2014-02-19}} ''A total of 22,477 Model S sedans were sold in 2013.''</ref> Tesla produced 7,535 units during the first quarter of 2014, and expected to produce 8,500 to 9,000 cars in the second quarter of 2014. As of early May 2014, the production rate was 700 cars per week.<ref name=Letter1Q2014>{{cite web |url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3152877106x0xS1193125-14-187459/1318605/filing.pdf |title=First Quarter 2014 Shareholder Letter |author=Tesla Motors |publisher=[[Tesla Motors]] |date=2014-05-07 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053451/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3152877106x0xS1193125-14-187459/1318605/filing.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{{asof|2015}}, about 1,000 cars are made per week,<ref name=te2015-05-02>{{cite news |first=Nikki |last=Gordon-Bloomfield |url=https://transportevolved.com/2015/05/06/tesla-motors-posts-q1-2015-losses-due-to-strong-dollar-high-capital-expenditures-hits-1000-carweek-model-s-production/ |title=Tesla Motors Posts Q1 2015 Losses, Due to Strong Dollar, High Capital Expenditures. Hits 1,000 Car/Week Model S Production |work=Transport Evolved |date=2015-05-06 |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref><ref name=engadget>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/05/20/tesla-lands-sudden-deal-with-toyota-will-build-model-s-sedan-in/ |title=Tesla lands sudden deal with Toyota, will build Model S sedan in Fremont NUMMI plant |first=Darren |last=Murph |publisher=Engadget |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2011-09-24}}</ref> mostly to pre-orders.<ref name=2015ecP8 /> Musk says they average around 20 changes to the S per week.<!--continuous development--><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/alternative/1411_2015_tesla_model_s_p85d_first_test/ |title=2015 Tesla Model S P85D First Test |first=Kim |last=Reynolds |journal=Motor Trend |date=2014-11-03 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>\n\nProduction of the [[Tesla Model X|Model X]] joined the Model S during 2015,<ref name=2015ecP15>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/15/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010002/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/15/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=15 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref> following a short reconfiguration of the production line in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla idles Fremont production line for Model X upgrade |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_26188834/tesla-idles-fremont-plant-model-x-suv-upgrade |website=San Jose Mercury |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2014-07-22}}</ref> The first Model X that didn't need corrections was made in April<!--29--> 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/05/05/tesla-model-3-manufacturing-process/ |title=With Model 3, Tesla will approach manufacturing in a new way |first=Sebastion |last=Blanco |work=Autoblog |date=2016-05-05 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Tesla moved some of [[Overhead crane|the equipment]] to their [[Tilburg]] final assembly plant in the [[Netherlands]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://cleantechnica.com/2015/12/19/tantalizing-tour-tesla-tilburg/ |title=Tantalizing Tour of Tesla in Tilburg |first=Kyle |last=Field |work=CleanTechnica |date=2015-12-19 |accessdate=2017-01-08 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, 2015, Tesla announced that it had delivered a total of 21,537 vehicles in the first half of 2015. All vehicles were manufactured at the Fremont plant.<ref name=tesla2015q2>{{cite web |url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=920434 |title=Tesla Delivers 11,507 Vehicles in Q2 of 2015 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2015-07-02 |accessdate=2015-07-08}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016 Tesla raised $1.46 billion in stock, of which $1.26 billion is to prepare production of the [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]] scheduled for late 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://electrek.co/2016/05/06/tesla-model-3-production-plan-federal-tax-credit/ |title=Tesla\u2019s new Model 3 production plan will optimize access to the federal tax credit |first=Fred |last=Lampert |work=Electrek |date=2016-05-06 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://electrek.co/2016/06/16/tesla-106-million-tax-break-expansion-fremont-factory-model-3/ |title=Tesla applied for a $106 million tax break on $1.26 billion expansion of Fremont Factory for the Model 3 |first=Fred |last=Lampert |work=Electrek |date=2016-05-16 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Changing from serially producing the Model S and X to the [[mass production]] of Model 3 is viewed by experts as a significant step.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |title=Tesla\u2019s supply chain set for a surge |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-07-26 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194902/http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live|quote=Getting from something like 50,000 to 500,000 units is a big, big step}}</ref> Tesla stated in May 2016 that it does not have that capability and needs to acquire it,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |title=Tesla warns supply chain issues could scupper its growth plans |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-05-11 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220195112/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live|quote= it has no experience in manufacturing vehicles at the volumes anticipated for the Model 3..  ..will need to develop \u201cefficient, automated, low-cost manufacturing capabilities, processes and supply chains necessary to support such volumes\u201d}}</ref> which it partly did with the acquisition of Grohmann Automation in 2016<ref name=Grohmann2>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-buys-automated-manufacturing-specialist-grohmann-engineering |title=Tesla buys automated manufacturing specialist Grohmann |first=Gareth |last=Tredway |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-11-08 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194319/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-buys-automated-manufacturing-specialist-grohmann-engineering |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live}}</ref> and purchase of mass production equipment. Whereas the Roadster was delayed by 9 months, the Model S more than six months, and the Model X more than 18 months,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-ramping-up-and-stepping-down |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160517142449/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-ramping-up-and-stepping-down |title=Tesla: ramping up and stepping down |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |date=2016-05-06 |archivedate=2016-05-17 |work=Automotive Logistics|accessdate=2016-12-20 |url-status= live}}</ref> analysts estimated in December 2016 that the Model 3 production preparation was on schedule for the second half of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://electrek.co/2016/12/20/tesla-model-3-on-track-2017-tesla-analysts/ |title=Tesla Model 3 on track for H2 2017, Model X production \u2018inconsistent\u2019, says TSLA analyst after meeting with management |date=2016-12-20 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |work=Electrek |access-date=2016-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2016, Tesla announced that it was consistently producing 2,000 vehicles per week at the end of Q2 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2564340823x0x903036/562D56A1-5426-4D79-8B99-3408D1B60226/Q2_16_Update_Letter_-_final.pdf |title=Tesla Second Quarter 2016 Update|date=2016-08-03|publisher=shareholder.com |access-date=2016-08-03|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160815100048/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2564340823x0x903036/562D56A1-5426-4D79-8B99-3408D1B60226/Q2_16_Update_Letter_-_final.pdf |archive-date=August 15, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.cnbc.com/2016/08/03/tesla-reports-second-quarter-earnings.html |title=Tesla misses Wall Street targets, but logs gains in vehicle production|last=Wang|first=Robert Ferris, Christine|date=2016-08-03 |website=CNBC |access-date=2016-08-03}}</ref> About 2,500 workers operate the day shift and 2,000 attend the [[Shift work|night shift]].<ref name=FremontMasterPlan/>\n\nTesla makes many parts itself, which is unusual in the auto business. Tesla also works with 300 suppliers around the world, of which 50 are in Northern California, and 10 in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/08/04/how-tesla-drives-manufacturing-bay-are-elon-musk.html |title=The Tesla Effect: How the cutting edge company became the most powerful engine in Bay Area manufacturing |first=Patrick |last=Hoge |work=BizJournal |date=2016-08-04 |access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref> Tesla's [[dashboard]] supplier SAS rents a 142,188-square-foot building near<!--5miles--> the factory, beginning in January 2017 with 200 employees<!--\"Tesla effect\"?-->.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/11/11/tesla-sas-eureka-landing.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161111161950/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/11/11/tesla-sas-eureka-landing.html |title=German automotive supplier signs massive lease near Tesla|first= Kevin |last=Truong |date=2016-11-11 |archivedate=2016-11-11 |work=[[American City Business Journals|San Francisco Business Times]] |accessdate=2016-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other suppliers to have opened facilities in the area to be close to Tesla include Eclipse Automation and Futuris Automotive Group<!--leather-->.<ref>McCall, Mark. \"[http://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2016/02/f29/DOE-LPO_Mini-Reports_004_ATVM-Driving-Economic-Growth_FINAL_Jan-2016.pdf Driving Economic Growth: ADVANCED TECHNOLOGY VEHICLES MANUFACTURING]\" January 2016</ref> Tesla produces many of its seats at its own seat factory a few miles south of the main factory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shahan |first1=Zachary |title=Tesla's Seat Heaven \u2014 Home Of Tesla's Cloud-Like Seats |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/22/teslas-seat-heaven-home-of-teslas-cloud-like-seats/ |website=CleanTechnica |date= 2019-04-22 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190423141428/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/22/teslas-seat-heaven-home-of-teslas-cloud-like-seats/ |archivedate= 2019-04-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Tesla implemented virus mitigation efforts in its [[Giga Shanghai|Shanghai]] and Fremont factories. Shanghai resumed production on February 10th, while the Fremont and [[Giga New York|New York factories]] were to reduce activity by March 24.<ref name=xinhua20200210>{{cite web |title=China Focus: Back to work, enterprises gradually resume operation amid epidemic outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/10/c_138771875.htm |website=www.xinhuanet.com |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref name=containvirus>{{cite web |last1=Alvarez |first1=Simon |title=Tesla China shares Giga Shanghai safety measures against COVID-19 virus |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-china-giga-shanghai-covid-19-fremont-factory-elon-musk/ |website=TESLARATI |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla announces factory shutdown starting on March 24 |url=https://electrek.co/2020/03/19/tesla-factory-shutdown-starting-march-24/ |website=[[Electrek]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tesla Model S manufacturing process==\n\n===Overview===\nThe manufacturing process uses more than 160 specialist robots, including 10 of the largest robots in the world,<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/> which are named after [[X-Men]] characters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.treehugger.com/cars/sneak-peak-teslas-california-factory-upgrade-which-includes-x-men-characters-climbing-plants-giant-robots-etc.html |title=Tesla's factory upgrade: X-Men characters, climbing plants, giant robots, murals, etc |first=Michael Graham |last=Richard |work=TreeHugger |date=2014-11-21 |accessdate=2015-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cleantechnica.com/2014/11/18/tesla-robots-get-x-men-names/ |title=Tesla Robots Get X-Men Names |first=Zachary |last=Shahan |work=Clean Technica |date=2014-11-18 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/video/at-tesla-workers-team-up-with-robot-superheroes/F9732D42-BAC6-47AE-B226-87E945966ADF.html |title=At Tesla, Workers Team Up With Robot Superheroes |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=2015-04-15 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Many of the Model S's unique components, including the [[battery pack]], battery module, and drive units are manufactured in-house. The plant has a high level of integration compared with other modern car assembly plants, with most processes taking place within the Tesla Factory. This includes most of the stamping and machining, painting, and some coding. The [[Machine press|hydraulic press lines used to stamp]] 5,000 body panels per day with a force of 10,000 tonnes,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.wired.co.uk/article/tesla-factory-interview |title=Building Tesla: inside Elon Musk's car factory of the future |first=Michael |last=Rundle |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |date=2016-01-12 |accessdate=2016-12-08 }}</ref> are the largest in North America and the 6th largest in the world.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\">{{cite web |title=Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble |url=http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/can-tesla-become-bigger-company-model-s-electric-car-thats-elon-musks-gamble |website=Autoweek.com |publisher=Autoweek |accessdate=2015-04-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304134808/http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/can-tesla-become-bigger-company-model-s-electric-car-thats-elon-musks-gamble |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status= live }}</ref> Around 60% of the car parts are sourced from [[North America]],<ref name=2015ecP14>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/14/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=14 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511214856/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/14/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archivedate=2015-05-11}}</ref> while Japan is the second-biggest source of components {{asof|2015|03|lc=yes}}.<!--battery cells?--><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/In-Gear/2015/0330/Tesla-pushes-investors-for-a-gigafactory-in-Japan |work= [[The Christian Science Monitor]] |first= Stephen |last= Edelstein |title= Tesla pushes investors for a gigafactory in Japan |date=2015-03-30 |accessdate=2015-05-21}}</ref> Design engineers also work at the factory itself, rather than a separate facility.<ref name=\"How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED)\"/><ref name=\"During summer factory upgrade, Tesla installed 10 of the largest robots in the world\">{{cite web |title=During summer factory upgrade, Tesla installed 10 of the largest robots in the world |url=http://electrek.co/2014/11/20/during-summer-factory-upgrade-tesla-installed-10-of-the-largest-robots-in-the-world/ |website=electrek.co |publisher=Electrek |accessdate=2015-04-26}}</ref>\n\nEach vehicle is made to order with a two to three-month wait time for delivery,<ref name=\"Electric Car Quality Tests , Tesla Motors Part 3 (WIRED)\">{{cite web |title=Electric Car Quality Tests , Tesla Motors Part 3 (WIRED) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVqlZO7tHFE |website=wired.com |publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> although individual vehicles only take between three and five days to complete the assembly process.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/> The [[assembly line]] moves at a speed of 5 [[Centimetre|cm]]/s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-tesla-factory-alien-dreadnought-2016-10 |title=Elon Musk: Tesla's factory will be an 'alien dreadnought' by 2018|first= Danielle |last=Muoio|date=2016-10-27 |work=Business Insider |accessdate=2016-11-14 }}</ref> Tesla prefers delivery by train rather than by truck, as costs and damages are less.<ref name=2015ecP8/>\n\n===Drive unit construction===\n\n====Motor construction====\n[[File:Tesla Visit 10 (9264760375).jpg|A complete [[Tesla Model S]] [[alternating current]] [[electric motor]] that has had a section removed from the [[stator]] to show the [[Rotor (electric)|rotor]] inside.|thumb]]\nThe [[alternating current]] [[electric motor]] is constructed in-house. The main components of the motor are the [[stator]] and [[Rotor (electric)|rotor]].<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nThe motor construction begins when a robot unspools and winds over {{convert|1/2|mi|km}} of copper wire per motor. It then pulls the copper wire into a stack. The motor has three phases and so requires three coils of copper.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> A worker then lengthens and straightens each bundle of wire and inserts the hydraulic lift to transfer the motor to the next station.\n\nA worker insulates each bundle of copper wire in a plastic sleeve to prevent the bundles from touching one another.  The ends of the bundles are then snipped to the correct length. Lugs are added and crimped to form attachment points for the motor's three phases.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> A specialized automatic sewing machine then binds the coils together to keep them in place, the increased tightness of the binding provided by a robotic sewing machine increases the efficiency of the motor. The stator is then encased in a two part epoxy resin to help in evenly distributing the motor's heat. The stator is now complete and is inserted into a heated metal case, locking the stator inside as the case cools.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nA worker uses a hoisting system to insert the rotor inside the stator completing the construction of the motor.\n\n=====Additional drive unit components=====\nA worker then installs the differential and other sections of the gearbox, attaching it together using bolts.  An air leak test is then conducted. The three phase tripole [[power inverter]] is then installed onto the top of the motor to convert [[direct current]] from the battery into alternating current for the motor to use. The motor then undergoes a series of automated tests taking 4 minutes to ensure correct function, and then is moved to the general assembly area to be installed into the car.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nThe power inverter is constructed from [[metal\u2013oxide\u2013semiconductor]] (MOS) [[power transistor]]s. Early Tesla vehicles used MOS-controlled [[insulated-gate bipolar transistor]]s (IGBTs), which have been replaced by [[silicon carbide]] (SiC) [[power MOSFET]]s ([[MOSFET|MOS field-effect transistors]]) in later Tesla vehicles since 2018.<ref name=\"pntpower\">{{cite news |last1=Avron |first1=Alex |title=Is Tesla's production creating a SiC MOSFET shortage? |url=https://www.pntpower.com/is-teslas-production-creating-a-sic-mosfet-shortage/ |accessdate=21 December 2019 |work=PntPower |date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Battery pack construction===\n[[File:Liion-18650-AA-battery.jpg|The Model S 85KWh battery pack uses 7,104 '[[18650]]' [[lithium-ion battery]] cells (right). A smaller [[AA battery]] is on the left for scale.|thumb|upright]]\n\nThe Model S 85s battery pack contains 7,104 '[[18650]]' [[lithium-ion battery]] cells in 16 modules<ref>{{cite web |last=Musk |first=Elon |title=Model S Fire |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/model-s-fire |publisher=[[Tesla Motors]] |accessdate=2014-02-20 |date=2013-10-04}}</ref> wired in series (14 in the flat section and two stacked on the front).<ref>{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Wayne |title=Tesla Model S: The battery pack |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-13746_7-20018836-48.html |publisher=C{{!}}Net|accessdate=2014-02-20|date=2010-10-06}}</ref> Each module contains six groups<ref>{{cite web |last=stopcrazypp |title=NHTSA Opened Up the Model S Battery Pack - Pics |url=http://www.teslamotorsclub.com/showthread.php/21850-NHTSA-Opened-Up-the-Model-S-Battery-Pack-Pics/page2?p=449465&viewfull=1#post449465 |work=Tesla Motors Club Forum |accessdate=2014-02-20 |quote=We know from the diagnosis screen that the 85&nbsp;kWh pack has 16 modules with 6 groups in series (so 96 groups in series):[https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-csWFYzE8OE8/UCnVgOsCo1I/AAAAAAAATUE/Ngjz-jlZMYc/w702-h498-no/IMG_0876.JPG]}}</ref> of 74 cells<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{US patent reference|number=8286743|y=2012|m=10|d=16|inventor=Rawlison, Peter Dore|title=Vehicle Battery Pack Ballistic Shield}}</ref> wired in parallel; the six groups are then wired in series within the module.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{US patent reference|number=2007009787|y=2007|m=1|d=11|title=Method and Apparatus for Mounting, Cooling, Connecting, and Protecting Batteries}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Beltran |first=Balbino A. |last2=Dunlap |first2=Michael L. |last3=Richardson |first3=Frank D. |title=REPORT NUMBER: NCAP305I-KAR-13-054 NEW CAR ASSESSMENT PROGRAM (NCAP) FMVSS NO. 305 INDICANT TEST TESLA MOTORS, INC. 2013 TESLA MODEL S 5-DOOR HATCHBACK NHTSA NUMBER: MD5001 |date=2013-08-07 |issue=NCAP305I-KAR-13-054 |page=A-13 |url=http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/database/aspx/searchmedia2.aspx?mediatype=r&LJC=8309&existphoto=Y&p_tstno=8309&existreport=Y&r_tstno=8309&existvideo=Y&v_tstno=8309&database=v&tstno=8309 |accessdate=2014-02-20 |publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation, National Highway Safety Adminitstration |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226120230/http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/database/aspx/searchmedia2.aspx?mediatype=r&LJC=8309&existphoto=Y&p_tstno=8309&existreport=Y&r_tstno=8309&existvideo=Y&v_tstno=8309&database=v&tstno=8309 |archivedate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref name=NYT062312>{{cite news |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/23/tesla-motors-launches-model-s-in-california/?ref=automobiles |title=Leaving Baggage On the Dock, a Flagship Departs From California |author=Josie Garthaite |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2012-06-23 |accessdate=2012-06-24}}</ref> {{asof|2012|06}} the battery pack uses modified [[Panasonic]] NCR18650A 3100[[Ampere-hour|mAh]] cells with nickel-cobalt-aluminum [[cathode]]s.<ref name=\"TMCharging\">{{cite web |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/models/charging#/highpower |title=Charge your Model S - Adapter Guide, High Power Charging, and Supercharge |publisher=Tesla Motors |accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref><ref name=USA062312>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2012/06/first-drive-teslas-model-s-electric-is-spectacular/1#.T-aCTdUV3nh |title=First Drive: Tesla's Model S electric is spectacular |author=Chris Woodyard |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2012-06-23 |accessdate=2012-06-24}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[commodity cell]]s, similar to those found in [[laptop]]s and [[mobile phone]]s, is in contrast to every other electric vehicle manufacturer who use specialized large format Li-Ion cells.<ref name=\"What Goes Into A Tesla Model S Battery--And What It May Cost\">{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Thomas |title=What Goes Into A Tesla Model S Battery--And What It May Cost |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1084682_what-goes-into-a-tesla-model-s-battery--and-what-it-may-cost |website=www.greencarreports.com |publisher=Green Car Reports |accessdate=2015-03-25}}</ref> The liquid-cooled battery pack uses an [[intumescent]] gel to aid in fireproofing and even heat distribution.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Body construction===\n\n====Aluminium coil blanking====\n98% of the Tesla Model S body is constructed from [[aluminium]]<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\">{{cite web |title=How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mzV7Y9B0tk |publisher=How Its Made |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> and is produced from between 50 and 60 separate coils of aluminium each for various components. The coils are unwound, flattened and cut in a blanking machine; additional cutting is also done using [[Laser cutting|laser cutter]]. The total weight of the aluminium used in the Model S is around\n{{convert|410|lb|kg}}.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/>\n\n====Tandem press lines====\n[[File:Stamp and Repeat (6858564222).jpg|thumb|left|Stacked side panels that have been formed on the tandem press line.]]\nA robot then transfers the aluminium blanks into the tandem press lines where the sheets are stamped into the various panels of the cars. The Schuler SMG hydraulic stamping press line is the largest in North America and the 6th largest in the world.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/> The presses use up to 11,000 [[ton-force]] to form the body panels; the upper section applies 1400 tonnes of downward force and the lower section 130 tonnes.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> The blank aluminium sheet is stretched over the lower [[Die (manufacturing)|draw die]] and openings are cut with robots transferring the panels between processes. The workers then inspect each panel to ensure correct pressing.  The parts are then stacked in frames and stored. The machines press one part every 6 seconds and create 5,000 parts per day.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\">{{cite web |title=How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_lfxPI5ObM |website=Wired.com |publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Drive unit installation===\nThe car is raised and the drive unit is installed into the rear [[axle]] assembly. The drive unit provides power directly to the [[wheel]]s without a [[drive shaft]].<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\n===Battery pack installation===\nThe [[battery pack]] weighs almost {{convert|1200|lb|kg}} and is delivered to the installation area and is raised into the car using a lift. Placing the battery pack under the cabin floor adds strength and rigidity to the car and lowers the vehicle's [[center of mass|center of gravity]]<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> to {{convert|18|in|cm|abbr=out|0}}.<ref name=rope>{{cite web |first=L. David |last=Roper |url=http://www.roperld.com/science/TeslaModelS.htm |title=Tesla Model S Data |accessdate=2015-04-05 <!--sources at page bottom-->}}</ref><ref name=sciAbuild>{{cite journal |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-tesla-motors-builds-the-safest-car-video/ |title=How Tesla Motors Builds One of the World's Safest Cars [Video] |first=David |last=Biello |journal=Scientific American |date=2013-09-23 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> A [[titanium]] plate is installed over the battery pack which protects it in the event of a high-speed collision and to protect from road debris.<ref>{{cite web |last=George |first=Patrick |title=The Tesla Model S: Now With Road Debris-Crushing Titanium! |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-s-now-with-road-debris-crushing-titani-1553544362 |work=Jalopnik |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |accessdate=2014-03-31 |date=2014-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Blanco |first=Sebastian |title=Tesla adds free titanium underbody shields to Model S to prevent fires |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2014/03/28/prevent-fire-tesla-adds-free-titanium-underbody-shields-model-s/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330071458/http://green.autoblog.com/2014/03/28/prevent-fire-tesla-adds-free-titanium-underbody-shields-model-s/ |archive-date=2014-03-30 |work=Autoblog Green |publisher=[[AOL Inc.]] |accessdate=2014-03-31 |date=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Safety incidents==\nOn April 1, 2019, Tesla reached a settlement with the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) over its mishandling of hazardous waste in 2017. Tesla allowed hazardous waste to accumulate on site without a permit beyond the allowed 90 days; the EPA found Tesla failed to \"promptly clean up flammable paint and or solvent mixtures\", left two {{convert|55|USgal|L|adj=on}} containers of hazardous waste open with \"no gasket or locking mechanism\", and violated air emission standards for three leaky transmission lines that the waste moved through.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/404019872/Tesla-EPA-settlement-for-hazardous-materials-violation |title=Tesla / EPA settlement for hazardous materials violation {{!}} Resource Conservation And Recovery Act {{!}} Hazardous Waste|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013 there was an accident when the low-pressure aluminum casting press failed, spilling molten metal on three workers and causing their clothing to catch fire. Tesla was fined {{USD}}89,000 by the [[California Department of Industrial Relations|California Division of Occupational Safety and Health]] for seven safety violations, six considered serious.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Motors faces $89,000 in fines for incident that injured workers at Fremont facility |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_25677719/tesla-motors-faces-fines-factory-violations-fremont |website=San Jose Mercury News |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2014-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Giga Nevada]]\n* [[Giga New York]]\n* [[Giga Shanghai]]\n* [[Giga Berlin]]\n* [[Tesla facilities in Tilburg]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*[http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/tesla-factory-birthplace-model-s The Tesla Factory: Birthplace of the Model S] Tesla Motors photo tour\n*[https://vimeo.com/43015249 Stamping], [https://vimeo.com/43083157 body], [https://vimeo.com/43505225 paint], [https://vimeo.com/109168998 automated motor production], [https://vimeo.com/43997600 assembly], [https://vimeo.com/106564929 factory upgrade] (official Tesla)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_lfxPI5ObM How Tesla Builds Electric Cars], A 3-part documentary on the Tesla Factory from [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'' magazine]]\n*[http://www.natgeotv.com/ca/megafactories/videos/brand-new-tesla-factory \"Brand New Tesla Factory\"], [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] video; {{youtube|kbusZ_iaUyE|Documentary}} by [[National Geographic Channel]] [[Ultimate Factories#Season 6 (2013)|Megafactories]]\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/403/nummi  NPR's This American Life's full hour story of the creation and demise of NUMMI - episode #403 ] from [[This American Life]]\n\n{{Tesla Motors}}\n\n{{coord|37|29|41.12|N|121|56|41.16|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Tesla factories]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle assembly plants in California]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Fremont, California]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established  in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Automobile manufacturing plant in south Fremont, California}}\n{{about|the Tesla factory in Fremont, CA, USA|the factory in Nevada|Gigafactory 1|the factory in Buffalo, NY|Gigafactory 2|the factory in Shanghai, China|Giga Shanghai|the factory in Tilburg, Netherlands|Tesla facilities in Tilburg|the planned factory in Berlin, Germany|Gigafactory 4}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox factory\n|name=Tesla Factory\n|image=File:Tesla_auto_bots.jpg\n|caption=[[Tesla Model S]] assembly at the Tesla Factory\n|location=[[Fremont, California]]\n|industry=[[Automotive industry]]\n|products=[[Tesla Model S]]<br>[[Tesla Model X]]<br>\n[[Tesla Model 3]]\n|employees=10,000\n|built={{start date|1962}} as [[Fremont Assembly]]<br>{{start date|2010}} as Tesla Factory\n|address=45000 Fremont Boulevard<br>[[Fremont, California]]  94538\n|owner=[[Tesla, Inc.]]|coordinates={{coord|37|29|41.12|N|121|56|41.16|W}}}}\n\nThe '''Tesla Factory''' is an [[automobile]] [[manufacturing]] [[factory|plant]] in [[Fremont, California]], operated by [[Tesla, Inc.]] The facility opened as the [[General Motors]] [[Fremont Assembly]] in 1962, and was later operated by [[NUMMI]], a former [[General Motors|GM]]\u2013[[Toyota]] joint venture.<ref name=\"sjbj\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2010/10/27/tesla-officially-replaces-nummi.html |first=Lisa |last=Sibley |title=Tesla officially replaces NUMMI in Fremont |date=2010-10-27}}</ref> Tesla took ownership in 2010.<ref name=\"tesla factory release\" /> The plant {{As of|2019|May|df=|alt=currently}} manufactures the [[Tesla Model S|Model S]], [[Tesla Model X|Model X]], and [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]], employing 10,000 people {{As of|2018|June|df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"SJ Merc June 2018 racism lawsuit\" />\n\n==Background==\nTesla had planned for an assembly factory in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], as a central location for shipping.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teslamotors.com/media/press_room.php?id=257 |title=Tesla Motors press release - announcement of Albuquerque plant |publisher=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406182037/http://www.teslamotors.com/media/press_room.php?id=257 |archivedate=2010-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Severns |first=Dave |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog1/?p=52 |title=Tesla Motors blog post regarding Albuquerque decision |publisher=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317081628/http://www.teslamotors.com/blog1/?p=52 |archivedate=2007-03-17}}</ref> Construction was supposed to begin in April 2007, but was canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2007/aug/21/editorial-dont-hold-your-breath-tesla-motors-plant/ |title=The Albuquerque Tribune Editorial: Don't hold your breath on Tesla Motors plant |publisher=Abqtrib.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214022134/http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2007/aug/21/editorial-dont-hold-your-breath-tesla-motors-plant/ |archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref> A separate [[greenfield project|greenfield]] factory to be built in [[San Jose, California]] was also announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_9745521 |title=Tesla to build electric car factory in Bay Area - San Jose Mercury News |publisher=Mercurynews.com |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120920174832/http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_9745521 |archivedate=2012-09-20}}</ref> However, the cost was prohibitive, and the company looked for alternatives. Tesla initially also dismissed NUMMI for being too big and costly.<ref name=odell/>\n\nSome of the current facility was operated as the GM [[Fremont Assembly]] from 1962 to 1982, and between 1984 and 2009 was used by New United Motor Manufacturing, Inc. ([[NUMMI]]),<ref name=aw2017-03/> a joint venture between [[General Motors]] and [[Toyota]],<ref name=\"sjbj\"/><ref name=\"How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED)\">{{cite web |title=How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TEReFPI4jSc |website=YouTube|publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> producing 357,809 cars and trucks in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://autointell.com/nao_companies/general_motors/gm-manufacturing/gm-nummi/gmnummi.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160314051152/http://autointell.com/nao_companies/general_motors/gm-manufacturing/gm-nummi/gmnummi.htm |title=GM Nummi Plant|archivedate=2016-03-14|accessdate=2016-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> Proposals to continue the site after 2010 included [[Aurica Motors|Aurica EVs]], state incentives to Toyota, and a stadium, but [[NUMMI#Alternatives to closure|none of them succeeded]]. In 2010 the mayor of Fremont viewed the site as dead.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nThe plant is located in the [[Fremont, California#South Fremont District|South Fremont District]] between the [[Warm Springs / South Fremont (BART station)|Warm Springs BART station]]<ref name=warmsprings>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2016/06/15/toll-brothers-buys-big-fremont-site-near-bart.html |title=Toll Brothers buys land near Fremont Warm Springs BART station |first=Nathan |last=Donato-Weinstein |work=Silicon Valley Business Journal |location=US |date=2016-06-15 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> and the [[California State Route 262]] connecting I880 and I680. [[Union Pacific Railroad]] has tracks at the plant<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vta.org/bart/missionwarren |title=Mission/Warren Area Improvements |publisher=Santa Clara Valley Transportation Authority |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2013/07/19/tesla-buys-big-chunk-of-fremont-land.html |title=Tesla Motors buys test track in 35-acre deal |first=Nathan |last=Donato-Weinstein |work=Silicon Valley Business Journal |location=US |date=2013-07-19 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> which carry finished cars.<ref name=2015ecP8>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/8/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010027/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/8/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=8 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref> [[Rail freight transport]] is also used to receive batteries and Model 3 drivetrains from Tesla's [[Gigafactory 1]]<!-- and other parts-->.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nevada/tesla-officials-show-progress-gigafactory-northern-nevada|title=Tesla officials show off progress at Gigafactory in Northern Nevada|first=SEAN WHALEY LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL CAPITAL |last=BUREAU|date=2016-03-18 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160803161348/http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nevada/tesla-officials-show-progress-gigafactory-northern-nevada |archivedate=2016-08-03 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2010, [[Tesla Inc.]] and Toyota announced a partnership to work on electric vehicle development and collaborate on the \"development of electric vehicles, parts, and production system and engineering support\". This included Tesla's partial purchase of the former NUMMI site, mainly consisting of the factory building,<ref name=\"sfbiz\">{{cite news |author=Lindsay Riddell |title=Tesla to buy NUMMI plant, build cars with Toyota |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2010/05/17/daily65.html |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=2010-04-20 |accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref><ref name=\"kvtu\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/23625639/detail.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523055832/http://www.ktvu.com/news/23625639/detail.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-05-23 |title=Tesla Wants NUMMI Operational By 2012 |work=KVTU.com |date=2010-05-21 |accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> for $42 million.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/05/27/BUL21DLN2C.DTL |title=Tesla paid only $42 million for Nummi plant |first=David R. |last=Baker |newspaper=[[San Francisco Gate]] |date=2010-04-28}}</ref><ref name=\"detnews\">{{cite news |last=Tierney |first=Christine |url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20100520/AUTO01/5200516/1148/Toyota-invests-in-Tesla-to-help-reopen-Calif.-plant |title=Toyota invests in Tesla to help reopen Calif. plant |newspaper=The Detroit News |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-05-22}}{{Dead link|date=April 2012}}</ref>\n\nTesla officially took possession of the site on October 19, 2010,<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news |author=PUI-WING TAM |title=Idle Fremont Plant Gears Up for Tesla |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704300604575554662948527140 |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2011-04-03 |quote=Parts of the Fremont facility will be mothballed since Tesla is only using a fraction of the space. \"When Nummi said it would close, the land was dead,\" says Fremont Mayor Bob Wasserman. When Tesla announced its Nummi deal in May, he says, \"the land became alive\" again |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150316123930/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704300604575554662948527140 |url-status=live |archive-date=2015-03-16 }}</ref> and opened it on October 27.<ref name=\"tesla factory release\">{{cite press_release | url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/releasedetail.cfm?releaseid=523911 | title=Tesla Motors Opens Tesla Factory - Home of the Model S | publisher=Tesla Motors | date=2010-10-27 | accessdate=2012-07-18}}</ref> The state of California has supported the renewal, expecting tax income from sustained jobs.<ref name=taxrebate1>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/la-fi-hy-musk-subsidies-box-20150530-story.html |title=Three companies, $4.9 billion in government support |author=Jerry Hirsch |date=2015-05-30 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2015-10-29 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151025213157/http://www.latimes.com/local/la-fi-hy-musk-subsidies-box-20150530-story.html |archivedate=2015-10-25 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=rtRebate>{{cite web |url=https://www.rt.com/usa/264065-musk-tesla-government-subsidies/ |title=Musk defends receiving $4.9 billion in government support for Tesla, SolarCity and SpaceX |work=RT English |accessdate=2015-10-29 }}</ref><ref>http://www.business.ca.gov/Portals/0/CA%20Competes/Docs/Agreements/FY1415P3Large/Tesla%20Motors,%20Inc.%20-%20CCTC%20Agreement.pdf</ref> The first retail delivery of the Tesla Model S took place during a special event at the Tesla Factory on June 22, 2012.<ref name=1stDelivery>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_20919722/silicon-valley-milestone-tesla-motors-begins-delivering-model?refresh=no |title=In a Silicon Valley milestone, Tesla Motors begins delivering Model S electric cars |author=John Boudreau |work=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2012-06-22}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Wide image|NUMMIplantMissionPeakPanorama 3199.jpg|800px|The former NUMMI (now Tesla) plant in Fremont, California}}\n\n==Facilities==\nNUMMI auctioned off<ref name=Maynards>{{cite web|url=http://www.equipmentappraisalsandauctions.com/new-united-motor-manufacturing.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613192846/http://www.equipmentappraisalsandauctions.com/new-united-motor-manufacturing.html |title=New United Motor Manufacturing Appraisals|work=Maynards |archivedate=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> the press lines, robots and other equipment to [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Kentucky|Toyota's]] [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Texas|other US]] [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Mississippi|factories]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20110918/OEM01/309189998/toyota-gave-old-robots-new-tools-to-trim-u.s.-camry-price-2 |title=Toyota gave old robots new tools to trim U.S. Camry price 2% |date=2011-09-18 |first=Alan |last=Ohnsman |work=[[Automotive News]] |accessdate=2017-06-05 |quote=Along with the production robots transferred to Toyota's Georgetown, Ky., plant that makes most of the Camrys sold in North America, Nummi equipment was also acquired by Toyota's San Antonio plant and electric-car maker Tesla Motors Inc.}}</ref><ref name=Hull2010>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/09/16/2010-tesla-gets-ready-to-take-over-the-former-nummi-auto-plant-in-fremont/ |title=2010: Tesla gets ready to take over the former NUMMI auto plant in Fremont |first=Dana |last=Hull |newspaper=The Mercury News |date=2010-09-16 |accessdate=2017-06-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502023843/http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/09/16/2010-tesla-gets-ready-to-take-over-the-former-nummi-auto-plant-in-fremont/ |archivedate=2017-05-02 |url-status=live |quote=The entire NUMMI facility covers about 370 acres. Tesla is buying 210 acres, a parcel that contains several buildings that have approximately 4.7 million square feet of floor space. NUMMI\u2019s existing press line will be taken apart and sent to Toyota\u2019s plant in Blue Springs, Miss.}}</ref> and Tesla purchased over $17 million of manufacturing equipment and spare parts in 2011, at significant discounts compared to new equipment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/11009706/1/tesla-motors-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2010-results.html |title=Tesla Motors Reports Fourth Quarter And Full Year 2010 Results |work=[[TheStreet]] |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2014-09-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727000648/https://www.thestreet.com/story/11009706/1/tesla-motors-reports-fourth-quarter-and-full-year-2010-results.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Additionally, Tesla bought a Schuler SMG hydraulic stamping press, worth $50 million, for $6 million, including shipping costs from Detroit.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/>\n\nThe factory was about 10 times the size Tesla initially needed,<ref name=odell>{{cite news |last=O'Dell |first=John |url=https://www.edmunds.com/autoobserver-archive/2010/03/would-be-ev-makers-plan-to-save-nummi-auto-plant-a-long-shot-at-best.html |title=Would-Be EV Maker's 'Plan' to Save NUMMI Auto Plant a Long Shot at Best |publisher=Green Car Advisor |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2010-04-02| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315144830/http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/03/would-be-ev-makers-plan-to-save-nummi-auto-plant-a-long-shot-at-best.html| archivedate=2010-03-15 | url-status=live |quote=Tesla had been wooed as a NUMMI tenant by politicians and economic development people .. But Tesla - which has all of about 550 employees and plans to ramp up to around 2,000 when it starts building its next vehicle in 2012, the Model S electric sedan - took a look at the costs involved and rejected the idea out of hand. The plant, said Straubel, is about 10 times the size of a facility Tesla would need to build even 20,000 cars a year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Inside Out \u2014 Tesla History From 7-Year Insider |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/11/09/tesla-inside-out-tesla-history-from-7-year-insider/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=9 November 2019 |quote=2012, he noted how empty and \u201cpost-apocalyptic\u201d the Fremont factory seemed. Tesla was only using about 10% of the space}}</ref><ref name=loveday2014/> and much of the {{convert|370|acre|sqft m2|adj=on}} site was unused in 2013, with most activity concentrated in the {{convert|5500000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} main building that does the final assembly of vehicles.<ref name=\"WSJ\" />\n\nVarious parts of the NUMMI plant were planned to be modified to support Tesla vehicle production. For example, the passenger vehicle paint equipment was to be extensively modified through late 2011;<ref name=\"WSJ\" />{{update after|2013|7|25}} converted from solvents to [[BASF]] water-based paint.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/> Two [[Electrostatic coating|paint lines]] (one car body, one component) were constructed from 2015.<!--capacity unclear--><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.eisenmann.com/en/media/press/press-releases/2015/2015_03_31_Tesla_Motors.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160405235244/http://www.eisenmann.com/en/media/press/press-releases/2015/2015_03_31_Tesla_Motors.html |title=Tesla Motors building the world\u2019s most advanced paint shop \u2013 with Eisenmann technology|date=2015-03-31 |archivedate=2016-04-05|publisher=Eisenmann |accessdate=2016-10-13 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |title=Tesla Motors Model 3 Equipment \"Already Online\" at Fremont Factory|work=The Country Caller|date=2016-08-04|accessdate=2016-10-13|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161013221553/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |archive-date=October 13, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3s-incorporated.com/projects/project/tesla-motors-paint-shop |title=Paint Shop Detection and Suppression Systems - 3S Incorporated|publisher= |accessdate=2016-10-13 }}</ref> By 2014, half of the factory area was in use.<ref name=loveday2014>{{cite web |last1=Loveday |first1=Eric |title=Tesla Motors Fremont Factory Usage Now Almost At 50% |url=https://insideevs.com/news/321993/tesla-motors-fremont-factory-usage-now-almost-at-50/ |website=InsideEVs |language=en |date=2014-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe floors, walls and ceiling are painted white with skylights and high-efficiency lighting to create an environment similar to a laboratory,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Factory |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/factory |website=Teslamotors.com |accessdate=2015-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.natgeotv.com/ca/megafactories/videos/brand-new-tesla-factory |title=Brand New Tesla Factory|work=National Geographic |date=2012 |accessdate=2017-06-15 <!-- mirror https://www.tesla.com/videos/national-geographic-megafactories-trailer -->}}</ref> and the production environment is cleaner and quieter than at NUMMI.<ref name=aw2017-03>{{cite magazine |url=http://autoweek.com/article/tesla/where-el-caminos-and-vibes-were-born-new-teslas-are-built-california |title=We visit the Tesla Factory, formerly Fremont Assembly and NUMMI |first=Murilee |last=Martin |magazine=[[Autoweek]] |date=2017-03-08 |accessdate=2017-04-08 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170329211120/http://autoweek.com/article/tesla/where-el-caminos-and-vibes-were-born-new-teslas-are-built-california |archive-date=2017-03-29 |url-status=live |quote=I spent a fair amount of time at NUMMI, and it seemed like a rackety, chaotic place on the production line .. Fast-forward 28 years, and the same facility is a brightly-lit, no-earplugs-needed, high-tech operation}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Tesla acquired an adjacent 35-acre property from Union Pacific Railroad for a test track.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Avalos|first1=George |title=Tesla buys land for test track in Fremont|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2013/07/19/tesla-buys-land-for-test-track-in-fremont/ |website=The Mercury News|accessdate=2018-02-17|date=2013-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=Jay|title=Picture (s) Of The Day: Tesla's Test Track In Fremont In Action|url= https://insideevs.com/picture-s-day-teslas-test-track-fremont-action/ |website=insideevs.com|accessdate=2018-02-17}}</ref>\n\nTesla built a casting foundry in [[Lathrop, California|Lathrop]] in 2015 supporting the Fremont production,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Acquires 431,000 Square Foot Facility In Lathrop, California - Begins \"Manufacturing Modifications\" Of Site |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-acquires-431000-square-foot-facility-lathrop-california-begins-manufacturing-modifications-site/ |last1=Loveday |first1=Eric |website=InsideEVs |date=2014-04-22 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EGHsDqwSY28 |title=Elon Musk is ecstatic about Powerwall demand - Tesla Q1 2015 Earnings call (2015) AUDIO}} at 1h02m</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/12/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150511004338/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/12/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=12 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/3151236-tesla-motors-tsla-elon-reeve-musk-on-q1-2015-results-earnings-call-transcript |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Elon Reeve Musk on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript |work=Seeking Alpha |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> and leased 1.3 million sq ft of warehouses in nearby [[Livermore, California|Livermore]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2017/03/23/real-deals-industrial-tesla-at-oaks-logistics.html |title=Tesla seals the deal on East Bay's largest industrial lease ever |last=Lucas |first=Scott |date=2017-03-24 |access-date=2017-06-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170613160747/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2017/03/23/real-deals-industrial-tesla-at-oaks-logistics.html |archive-date=2017-06-13 |url-status=live |quote=It leased 1.3 million square feet spread across three buildings}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, there were 4,500 parking spaces,<ref name=FremontMasterPlan/> and Tesla purchased a neighboring 25-acre site<ref name=sfc2016-10-07/> from housing developer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/print-edition/2016/04/29/warm-springs-district-fremont-lennar-homes-office.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161013105227/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/print-edition/2016/04/29/warm-springs-district-fremont-lennar-homes-office.html |title=Lennar plans huge R&D, housing complex at Warm Springs 'innovation district' near Tesla plant in Fremont |date=2016-04-29|archivedate=2016-10-13 |work=San Francisco Business Times|accessdate=2016-10-13 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lennar Corporation|Lennar]]. Tesla announced in August 2017 it won approval from the Fremont City Council to double the size of the facility with about 4.6 million new square feet of space.<ref name=\"eastbaytimes.com\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/08/10/tesla-factory-launches-expansion-that-could-double-its-size/ |title=Tesla factory launches expansion that could double its size|date=2017-08-11|website=East Bay Times|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> Tesla also planned to expand production capacity five-fold to 500,000 vehicles per year by 2018,<ref name=\"eastbaytimes.com\"/> or 10,000 units per week.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.thedrive.com/sheetmetal/13594/tesla-continues-growth-to-double-its-fremont-plant-in-size |title=Tesla Continues Growth to Double its Fremont Plant in Size|last=Stumpf|first=Rob |work=The Drive|access-date=2017-08-21 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Employees==\nTesla started production with 1,000 workers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Tesla-starts-delivery-out-of-former-Nummi-plant-3653530.php |title=Tesla starts delivery out of former Nummi plant |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=David R. |last=Baker |date=2012-06-22}}</ref> By 2013, this had risen to 3,000,<ref>{{cite web |title=Peek Inside Tesla\u2019s Robotic Factory |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/07/tesla-plant-video/ |website=Wired |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2013-07-16}}</ref> and to 6,000 people in June 2016.<ref name=employees>{{cite news |url=http://www.thecountrycaller.com/40182-tesla-motors-tsla-workers-being-contacted-by-uaw-for-union-formation/ |title=Tesla Motors Inc Workers Being Contacted by UAW For Union Formation |first=Angela |last=Campbell |work=The Country Caller |location=US |date=2016-06-09 |access-date=2016-07-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716082915/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/40182-tesla-motors-tsla-workers-being-contacted-by-uaw-for-union-formation/ |archivedate=2016-07-16}}</ref> In 2016, preparing for Model 3 production, Tesla planned to increase their work force to about 9,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconvalley.com/2016/12/08/fremont-city-council-approves-major-tesla-facility-expansion-plan/ |title=Fremont: City Council approves major Tesla facility expansion plan |first=Joseph |last=Geha |work=Silicon Valley |date=2016-12-08 |accessdate=2016-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fremontca.viebit.com/player.php?hash=agZlS6YYsCie |title=Video: Planning Commission Meeting, December 6, 2016. Time 1:40:20 and 2:16 |publisher=|date=2016-12-06 |accessdate=2017-01-17 }}</ref><ref name=FremontMasterPlan>[http://www.sfchronicle.com/file/178/7/1787-_16-0830%20Tesla%20Master%20Plan%20Final%20copy.pdf Master plan Tesla, Warm Springs. Summer 2016] [https://web.archive.org/web/20161008144132/http://www.sfchronicle.com/file/178/7/1787-_16-0830%20Tesla%20Master%20Plan%20Final%20copy.pdf Archive]</ref><ref name=sfc2016-10-07>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/New-Tesla-plan-could-double-size-of-Fremont-9936003.php |title=Tesla\u2019s new long-range plan could double size of Fremont factory|date=2016-10-07|work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2016/10/07/a-gigafactory-california-style-tesla-seeks-to-double-size-of-us-auto-plant/ |title=A Gigafactory, California Style? Tesla Seeks To Double Size of US Auto Plant|date=2016-10-07 |work=Forbes|accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fremontcityca.iqm2.com/Citizens/FileOpen.aspx?Type=1&ID=1338&Inline=True |title=Fremont Planning Commission Agenda |last=|first=|date=2016-10-13 |website=|publisher=Fremont Planning Commission |access-date=2017-01-17 |quote=File size=64 MB }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fremontca.viebit.com/player.php?hash=IKJWDr1IEupJ |title=Video: Planning Commission Meeting, October 27, 2016. Time 10:40 to 58:40|publisher=|date=2016-10-27 |accessdate=2017-01-17 }}</ref> In fall of 2017, Tesla employed some 10,000 at the Fremont plant,<ref name=\"SJ Merc Oct. 2017 hundreds fired after performance reviews\">{{cite web |last1=Hansen |first1=Louis |title=Tesla fires hundreds after company-wide performance reviews |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/10/13/4819750/ |website=The Mercury News |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2017-10-13}}</ref> a number still being shared in June 2018.<ref name=\"SJ Merc June 2018 racism lawsuit\">{{cite web |last1=Baron |first1=Ethan |title=Tesla fails in bid to push racism lawsuit into arbitration |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/06/04/tesla-fails-in-bid-to-push-racism-lawsuit-into-arbitration/ |website=The Mercury News |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Tesla employees, the company uses contractors for various functions. In May 2018, Elon Musk, in an apparent goal of reducing dead weight and raising efficiency and quality within its operation, decided to cut contractors and sub-contractors, ordering staff to justify and personally vouch for contractors worth keeping.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dellinger |first1=AJ |title=Tesla Will Lock Out Contractors on Monday Unless Employees Vouch For Them |url=https://gizmodo.com/tesla-will-lock-out-contractors-on-monday-unless-employ-1825812405 |website=Gizmodo |accessdate=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Elektrek May 2018 contractor justification\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla starts brutal review of contractors, firing everyone that is not vouched for by an employee |url=https://electrek.co/2018/05/06/tesla-brutal-review-contractors-firing-vouching-employee/ |website=Electrek |accessdate=2018-06-04 |date=2018-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:New Teslas at the factory.jpg|thumb|New [[Tesla Model S]] cars at the Tesla Factory in 2012]]\n\nThe plant's first [[series production]] vehicle is the [[Tesla Model S]] full-sized [[Battery electric vehicle|battery electric]] [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]].\n\nIn 2011, Tesla transitioned from 20 hand-assembled \"alpha builds\" to 50 \"beta builds\",<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gigaom.com/2011/03/17/photos-inside-teslas-model-s-alpha-workshop/ |title=PHOTOS: Inside Tesla\u2019s Model S Alpha Workshop|date=2011-03-17 |work=gigaom.com |accessdate=2017-06-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151204205900/https://gigaom.com/2011/03/17/photos-inside-teslas-model-s-alpha-workshop/ |archive-date=2015-12-04 |url-status= live }}</ref> production-validation vehicles built entirely at the Tesla Factory. These cars would also be used for system integration, engineering testing, and federal crash-testing and certification.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/autopia/2011/01/tesla-wants-some-engineering-cred |title=Tesla Wants Some Engineering Cred |first=Chuck |last=Squatriglia |work=[[Wired.com]] |date=2011-01-06}}</ref> Tesla expected to produce about 5,000 Model S sedans in 2012, with production ramping up to 20,000 in 2013 if necessary.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Ohnsman |title=Tesla Model S Assembly to Begin With Highest-Priced Version |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/tesla-says-model-s-production-to-begin-with-highest-priced-model.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110311153747/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/tesla-says-model-s-production-to-begin-with-highest-priced-model.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-03-11 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=2010-03-07 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://europe.autonews.com/article/20170102/ANE/161219895 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170109132511/http://europe.autonews.com/article/20170102/ANE/161219895 |title=Tesla Model S assembly to begin with highest-priced version |date=2011-03-07 |archivedate=2017-01-09 |newspaper=Automotive News|accessdate=2017-01-09 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first retail delivery of the Model S took place during a special event held at the Tesla Factory on June 22, 2012.<ref name=1stDelivery/> Production grew from 15\u201320 cars completed/week in August 2012<ref name=\"InsideTesla\">{{cite web |last=Blankenship |first=George |title=Inside Tesla |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/inside-tesla-082112 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2012-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> to over 200 by November 5<ref>{{cite web |last=Tesla Motors |title=Tesla Motors, Inc. \u2013 Third Quarter 2012 Shareholder Letter |url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1193125-12-450383&CIK=1318605 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2012-11-05 |accessdate=2012-12-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160502145601/http://ir.teslamotors.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1193125-12-450383&CIK=1318605 |archive-date=May 2, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and 400 by late December.<ref name=Sales2012>{{cite web |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2013/02/20/tesla-delivered-2-650-model-s-evs-last-year-musk-confident-of-p/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160417062435/http://www.autoblog.com/2013/02/20/tesla-delivered-2-650-model-s-evs-last-year-musk-confident-of-p/ |archive-date=2016-04-17 |title=Tesla delivered 2,650 Model S EVs last year, Musk confident of profit in Q1 and beyond |author=Domenick Yoney |publisher=Autoblog |date=2013-02-20 |accessdate=2013-03-10}} Around 2,650 Model S cars were delivered in the U.S. during 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.treehugger.com/cars/teslas-factory-reaches-20000-model-s-year-run-rate.html |title=Tesla Reaches 20,000 Unit Production Rate Annually for Model S |author=Michael Graham Richard |work=treehugger.com |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref> In late December Tesla revised their 2012 delivery projections down to 2,500 cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Make Way for Kilowatts: A Growing-Up Year for Plug-Ins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/23/automobiles/a-growing-up-year-for-plug-ins.html?_r=0 |work=New York Times |accessdate=2012-12-24 |date=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n\nDeliveries reached 6,892 units in the last three months of 2013.<ref name=Tesla4Q2013>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-02-19/teslas-stock-remains-electric-on-higher-sales-forecast |title=Tesla's Stock Remains Electric on Higher Sales Forecast |author=Ashlee Vance |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |date=2014-02-19 |accessdate=2014-02-19}}</ref> In December 2013, California announced it would give Tesla a US$34.7 million tax break to expand production by an estimated 35,000 vehicles annually from its Fremont, California plant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1089205_tesla-to-add-production-capacity-for-35000-more-electric-cars |title=Tesla To Add Production Capacity For 35,000 More Electric Cars |author=Antony Ingram |work=greencarreports.com |date=2013-12-18 |accessdate=2013-12-18}}</ref>\n\nTesla announced that production was expected to climb from 600 cars per week in early 2014 to about 1,000 units per week by year-end.<ref name=Tesla2013Sales>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hy-fourth-quarter-loss-telsa-20140219,0,6840087,full.story |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160124104551/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hy-fourth-quarter-loss-telsa-20140219-story.html |archive-date=2016-01-24 |title=Tesla Motors ends year with higher sales but still a big loss |author=Jerry Hirsch |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2014-02-19 |accessdate=2014-02-19}} ''A total of 22,477 Model S sedans were sold in 2013.''</ref> Tesla produced 7,535 units during the first quarter of 2014, and expected to produce 8,500 to 9,000 cars in the second quarter of 2014. As of early May 2014, the production rate was 700 cars per week.<ref name=Letter1Q2014>{{cite web |url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3152877106x0xS1193125-14-187459/1318605/filing.pdf |title=First Quarter 2014 Shareholder Letter |author=Tesla Motors |publisher=[[Tesla Motors]] |date=2014-05-07 |accessdate=2014-06-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053451/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3152877106x0xS1193125-14-187459/1318605/filing.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{{asof|2015}}, about 1,000 cars are made per week,<ref name=te2015-05-02>{{cite news |first=Nikki |last=Gordon-Bloomfield |url=https://transportevolved.com/2015/05/06/tesla-motors-posts-q1-2015-losses-due-to-strong-dollar-high-capital-expenditures-hits-1000-carweek-model-s-production/ |title=Tesla Motors Posts Q1 2015 Losses, Due to Strong Dollar, High Capital Expenditures. Hits 1,000 Car/Week Model S Production |work=Transport Evolved |date=2015-05-06 |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref><ref name=engadget>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/05/20/tesla-lands-sudden-deal-with-toyota-will-build-model-s-sedan-in/ |title=Tesla lands sudden deal with Toyota, will build Model S sedan in Fremont NUMMI plant |first=Darren |last=Murph |publisher=Engadget |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2011-09-24}}</ref> mostly to pre-orders.<ref name=2015ecP8 /> Musk says they average around 20 changes to the S per week.<!--continuous development--><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/alternative/1411_2015_tesla_model_s_p85d_first_test/ |title=2015 Tesla Model S P85D First Test |first=Kim |last=Reynolds |journal=Motor Trend |date=2014-11-03 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>\n\nProduction of the [[Tesla Model X|Model X]] joined the Model S during 2015,<ref name=2015ecP15>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/15/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010002/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/15/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-11 |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=15 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11}}</ref> following a short reconfiguration of the production line in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla idles Fremont production line for Model X upgrade |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_26188834/tesla-idles-fremont-plant-model-x-suv-upgrade |website=San Jose Mercury |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2014-07-22}}</ref> The first Model X that didn't need corrections was made in April<!--29--> 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/05/05/tesla-model-3-manufacturing-process/ |title=With Model 3, Tesla will approach manufacturing in a new way |first=Sebastion |last=Blanco |work=Autoblog |date=2016-05-05 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Tesla moved some of [[Overhead crane|the equipment]] to their [[Tilburg]] final assembly plant in the [[Netherlands]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://cleantechnica.com/2015/12/19/tantalizing-tour-tesla-tilburg/ |title=Tantalizing Tour of Tesla in Tilburg |first=Kyle |last=Field |work=CleanTechnica |date=2015-12-19 |accessdate=2017-01-08 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, 2015, Tesla announced that it had delivered a total of 21,537 vehicles in the first half of 2015. All vehicles were manufactured at the Fremont plant.<ref name=tesla2015q2>{{cite web |url=http://ir.teslamotors.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=920434 |title=Tesla Delivers 11,507 Vehicles in Q2 of 2015 |publisher=Tesla Motors |date=2015-07-02 |accessdate=2015-07-08}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016 Tesla raised $1.46 billion in stock, of which $1.26 billion is to prepare production of the [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]] scheduled for late 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://electrek.co/2016/05/06/tesla-model-3-production-plan-federal-tax-credit/ |title=Tesla\u2019s new Model 3 production plan will optimize access to the federal tax credit |first=Fred |last=Lampert |work=Electrek |date=2016-05-06 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://electrek.co/2016/06/16/tesla-106-million-tax-break-expansion-fremont-factory-model-3/ |title=Tesla applied for a $106 million tax break on $1.26 billion expansion of Fremont Factory for the Model 3 |first=Fred |last=Lampert |work=Electrek |date=2016-05-16 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Changing from serially producing the Model S and X to the [[mass production]] of Model 3 is viewed by experts as a significant step.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |title=Tesla\u2019s supply chain set for a surge |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-07-26 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194902/http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live|quote=Getting from something like 50,000 to 500,000 units is a big, big step}}</ref> Tesla stated in May 2016 that it does not have that capability and needs to acquire it,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |title=Tesla warns supply chain issues could scupper its growth plans |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-05-11 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220195112/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live|quote= it has no experience in manufacturing vehicles at the volumes anticipated for the Model 3..  ..will need to develop \u201cefficient, automated, low-cost manufacturing capabilities, processes and supply chains necessary to support such volumes\u201d}}</ref> which it partly did with the acquisition of Grohmann Automation in 2016<ref name=Grohmann2>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-buys-automated-manufacturing-specialist-grohmann-engineering |title=Tesla buys automated manufacturing specialist Grohmann |first=Gareth |last=Tredway |work=Automotive Logistics |date=2016-11-08 |accessdate=2016-12-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194319/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-buys-automated-manufacturing-specialist-grohmann-engineering |archive-date=2016-12-20 |url-status= live}}</ref> and purchase of mass production equipment. Whereas the Roadster was delayed by 9 months, the Model S more than six months, and the Model X more than 18 months,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-ramping-up-and-stepping-down |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160517142449/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-ramping-up-and-stepping-down |title=Tesla: ramping up and stepping down |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |date=2016-05-06 |archivedate=2016-05-17 |work=Automotive Logistics|accessdate=2016-12-20 |url-status= live}}</ref> analysts estimated in December 2016 that the Model 3 production preparation was on schedule for the second half of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://electrek.co/2016/12/20/tesla-model-3-on-track-2017-tesla-analysts/ |title=Tesla Model 3 on track for H2 2017, Model X production \u2018inconsistent\u2019, says TSLA analyst after meeting with management |date=2016-12-20 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |work=Electrek |access-date=2016-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2016, Tesla announced that it was consistently producing 2,000 vehicles per week at the end of Q2 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2564340823x0x903036/562D56A1-5426-4D79-8B99-3408D1B60226/Q2_16_Update_Letter_-_final.pdf |title=Tesla Second Quarter 2016 Update|date=2016-08-03|publisher=shareholder.com |access-date=2016-08-03|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160815100048/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2564340823x0x903036/562D56A1-5426-4D79-8B99-3408D1B60226/Q2_16_Update_Letter_-_final.pdf |archive-date=August 15, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.cnbc.com/2016/08/03/tesla-reports-second-quarter-earnings.html |title=Tesla misses Wall Street targets, but logs gains in vehicle production|last=Wang|first=Robert Ferris, Christine|date=2016-08-03 |website=CNBC |access-date=2016-08-03}}</ref> About 2,500 workers operate the day shift and 2,000 attend the [[Shift work|night shift]].<ref name=FremontMasterPlan/>\n\nTesla makes many parts itself, which is unusual in the auto business. Tesla also works with 300 suppliers around the world, of which 50 are in Northern California, and 10 in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/08/04/how-tesla-drives-manufacturing-bay-are-elon-musk.html |title=The Tesla Effect: How the cutting edge company became the most powerful engine in Bay Area manufacturing |first=Patrick |last=Hoge |work=BizJournal |date=2016-08-04 |access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref> Tesla's [[dashboard]] supplier SAS rents a 142,188-square-foot building near<!--5miles--> the factory, beginning in January 2017 with 200 employees<!--\"Tesla effect\"?-->.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/11/11/tesla-sas-eureka-landing.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161111161950/http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2016/11/11/tesla-sas-eureka-landing.html |title=German automotive supplier signs massive lease near Tesla|first= Kevin |last=Truong |date=2016-11-11 |archivedate=2016-11-11 |work=[[American City Business Journals|San Francisco Business Times]] |accessdate=2016-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other suppliers to have opened facilities in the area to be close to Tesla include Eclipse Automation and Futuris Automotive Group<!--leather-->.<ref>McCall, Mark. \"[http://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2016/02/f29/DOE-LPO_Mini-Reports_004_ATVM-Driving-Economic-Growth_FINAL_Jan-2016.pdf Driving Economic Growth: ADVANCED TECHNOLOGY VEHICLES MANUFACTURING]\" January 2016</ref> Tesla produces many of its seats at its own seat factory a few miles south of the main factory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shahan |first1=Zachary |title=Tesla's Seat Heaven \u2014 Home Of Tesla's Cloud-Like Seats |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/22/teslas-seat-heaven-home-of-teslas-cloud-like-seats/ |website=CleanTechnica |date= 2019-04-22 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190423141428/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/22/teslas-seat-heaven-home-of-teslas-cloud-like-seats/ |archivedate= 2019-04-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Tesla implemented virus mitigation efforts in its [[Giga Shanghai|Shanghai]] and Fremont factories. Shanghai resumed production on February 10th, while the Fremont and [[Giga New York|New York factories]] were to reduce activity by March 24.<ref name=xinhua20200210>{{cite web |title=China Focus: Back to work, enterprises gradually resume operation amid epidemic outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/10/c_138771875.htm |website=www.xinhuanet.com |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref name=containvirus>{{cite web |last1=Alvarez |first1=Simon |title=Tesla China shares Giga Shanghai safety measures against COVID-19 virus |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-china-giga-shanghai-covid-19-fremont-factory-elon-musk/ |website=TESLARATI |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla announces factory shutdown starting on March 24 |url=https://electrek.co/2020/03/19/tesla-factory-shutdown-starting-march-24/ |website=[[Electrek]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tesla Model S manufacturing process==\n\n===Overview===\nThe manufacturing process uses more than 160 specialist robots, including 10 of the largest robots in the world,<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/> which are named after [[X-Men]] characters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.treehugger.com/cars/sneak-peak-teslas-california-factory-upgrade-which-includes-x-men-characters-climbing-plants-giant-robots-etc.html |title=Tesla's factory upgrade: X-Men characters, climbing plants, giant robots, murals, etc |first=Michael Graham |last=Richard |work=TreeHugger |date=2014-11-21 |accessdate=2015-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cleantechnica.com/2014/11/18/tesla-robots-get-x-men-names/ |title=Tesla Robots Get X-Men Names |first=Zachary |last=Shahan |work=Clean Technica |date=2014-11-18 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/video/at-tesla-workers-team-up-with-robot-superheroes/F9732D42-BAC6-47AE-B226-87E945966ADF.html |title=At Tesla, Workers Team Up With Robot Superheroes |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=2015-04-15 |accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref> Many of the Model S's unique components, including the [[battery pack]], battery module, and drive units are manufactured in-house. The plant has a high level of integration compared with other modern car assembly plants, with most processes taking place within the Tesla Factory. This includes most of the stamping and machining, painting, and some coding. The [[Machine press|hydraulic press lines used to stamp]] 5,000 body panels per day with a force of 10,000 tonnes,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.wired.co.uk/article/tesla-factory-interview |title=Building Tesla: inside Elon Musk's car factory of the future |first=Michael |last=Rundle |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |date=2016-01-12 |accessdate=2016-12-08 }}</ref> are the largest in North America and the 6th largest in the world.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\">{{cite web |title=Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble |url=http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/can-tesla-become-bigger-company-model-s-electric-car-thats-elon-musks-gamble |website=Autoweek.com |publisher=Autoweek |accessdate=2015-04-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304134808/http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/can-tesla-become-bigger-company-model-s-electric-car-thats-elon-musks-gamble |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status= live }}</ref> Around 60% of the car parts are sourced from [[North America]],<ref name=2015ecP14>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/14/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |title=Tesla Motors (TSLA) Earnings Report: Q1 2015 Conference Call Transcript |work=TheStreet |page=14 |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511214856/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13142191/14/tesla-motors-tsla-earnings-report-q1-2015-conference-call-transcript.html |archivedate=2015-05-11}}</ref> while Japan is the second-biggest source of components {{asof|2015|03|lc=yes}}.<!--battery cells?--><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/In-Gear/2015/0330/Tesla-pushes-investors-for-a-gigafactory-in-Japan |work= [[The Christian Science Monitor]] |first= Stephen |last= Edelstein |title= Tesla pushes investors for a gigafactory in Japan |date=2015-03-30 |accessdate=2015-05-21}}</ref> Design engineers also work at the factory itself, rather than a separate facility.<ref name=\"How Tesla Builds Electric Cars , Tesla Motors Part 2 (WIRED)\"/><ref name=\"During summer factory upgrade, Tesla installed 10 of the largest robots in the world\">{{cite web |title=During summer factory upgrade, Tesla installed 10 of the largest robots in the world |url=http://electrek.co/2014/11/20/during-summer-factory-upgrade-tesla-installed-10-of-the-largest-robots-in-the-world/ |website=electrek.co |publisher=Electrek |accessdate=2015-04-26}}</ref>\n\nEach vehicle is made to order with a two to three-month wait time for delivery,<ref name=\"Electric Car Quality Tests , Tesla Motors Part 3 (WIRED)\">{{cite web |title=Electric Car Quality Tests , Tesla Motors Part 3 (WIRED) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVqlZO7tHFE |website=wired.com |publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> although individual vehicles only take between three and five days to complete the assembly process.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/> The [[assembly line]] moves at a speed of 5 [[Centimetre|cm]]/s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-tesla-factory-alien-dreadnought-2016-10 |title=Elon Musk: Tesla's factory will be an 'alien dreadnought' by 2018|first= Danielle |last=Muoio|date=2016-10-27 |work=Business Insider |accessdate=2016-11-14 }}</ref> Tesla prefers delivery by train rather than by truck, as costs and damages are less.<ref name=2015ecP8/>\n\n===Drive unit construction===\n\n====Motor construction====\n[[File:Tesla Visit 10 (9264760375).jpg|A complete [[Tesla Model S]] [[alternating current]] [[electric motor]] that has had a section removed from the [[stator]] to show the [[Rotor (electric)|rotor]] inside.|thumb]]\nThe [[alternating current]] [[electric motor]] is constructed in-house. The main components of the motor are the [[stator]] and [[Rotor (electric)|rotor]].<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nThe motor construction begins when a robot unspools and winds over {{convert|1/2|mi|km}} of copper wire per motor. It then pulls the copper wire into a stack. The motor has three phases and so requires three coils of copper.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> A worker then lengthens and straightens each bundle of wire and inserts the hydraulic lift to transfer the motor to the next station.\n\nA worker insulates each bundle of copper wire in a plastic sleeve to prevent the bundles from touching one another.  The ends of the bundles are then snipped to the correct length. Lugs are added and crimped to form attachment points for the motor's three phases.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> A specialized automatic sewing machine then binds the coils together to keep them in place, the increased tightness of the binding provided by a robotic sewing machine increases the efficiency of the motor. The stator is then encased in a two part epoxy resin to help in evenly distributing the motor's heat. The stator is now complete and is inserted into a heated metal case, locking the stator inside as the case cools.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nA worker uses a hoisting system to insert the rotor inside the stator completing the construction of the motor.\n\n=====Additional drive unit components=====\nA worker then installs the differential and other sections of the gearbox, attaching it together using bolts.  An air leak test is then conducted. The three phase tripole [[power inverter]] is then installed onto the top of the motor to convert [[direct current]] from the battery into alternating current for the motor to use. The motor then undergoes a series of automated tests taking 4 minutes to ensure correct function, and then is moved to the general assembly area to be installed into the car.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\nThe power inverter is constructed from [[metal\u2013oxide\u2013semiconductor]] (MOS) [[power transistor]]s. Early Tesla vehicles used MOS-controlled [[insulated-gate bipolar transistor]]s (IGBTs), which have been replaced by [[silicon carbide]] (SiC) [[power MOSFET]]s ([[MOSFET|MOS field-effect transistors]]) in later Tesla vehicles since 2018.<ref name=\"pntpower\">{{cite news |last1=Avron |first1=Alex |title=Is Tesla's production creating a SiC MOSFET shortage? |url=https://www.pntpower.com/is-teslas-production-creating-a-sic-mosfet-shortage/ |accessdate=21 December 2019 |work=PntPower |date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Battery pack construction===\n[[File:Liion-18650-AA-battery.jpg|The Model S 85KWh battery pack uses 7,104 '[[18650]]' [[lithium-ion battery]] cells (right). A smaller [[AA battery]] is on the left for scale.|thumb|upright]]\n\nThe Model S 85s battery pack contains 7,104 '[[18650]]' [[lithium-ion battery]] cells in 16 modules<ref>{{cite web |last=Musk |first=Elon |title=Model S Fire |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/model-s-fire |publisher=[[Tesla Motors]] |accessdate=2014-02-20 |date=2013-10-04}}</ref> wired in series (14 in the flat section and two stacked on the front).<ref>{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Wayne |title=Tesla Model S: The battery pack |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-13746_7-20018836-48.html |publisher=C{{!}}Net|accessdate=2014-02-20|date=2010-10-06}}</ref> Each module contains six groups<ref>{{cite web |last=stopcrazypp |title=NHTSA Opened Up the Model S Battery Pack - Pics |url=http://www.teslamotorsclub.com/showthread.php/21850-NHTSA-Opened-Up-the-Model-S-Battery-Pack-Pics/page2?p=449465&viewfull=1#post449465 |work=Tesla Motors Club Forum |accessdate=2014-02-20 |quote=We know from the diagnosis screen that the 85&nbsp;kWh pack has 16 modules with 6 groups in series (so 96 groups in series):[https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-csWFYzE8OE8/UCnVgOsCo1I/AAAAAAAATUE/Ngjz-jlZMYc/w702-h498-no/IMG_0876.JPG]}}</ref> of 74 cells<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{US patent reference|number=8286743|y=2012|m=10|d=16|inventor=Rawlison, Peter Dore|title=Vehicle Battery Pack Ballistic Shield}}</ref> wired in parallel; the six groups are then wired in series within the module.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{US patent reference|number=2007009787|y=2007|m=1|d=11|title=Method and Apparatus for Mounting, Cooling, Connecting, and Protecting Batteries}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Beltran |first=Balbino A. |last2=Dunlap |first2=Michael L. |last3=Richardson |first3=Frank D. |title=REPORT NUMBER: NCAP305I-KAR-13-054 NEW CAR ASSESSMENT PROGRAM (NCAP) FMVSS NO. 305 INDICANT TEST TESLA MOTORS, INC. 2013 TESLA MODEL S 5-DOOR HATCHBACK NHTSA NUMBER: MD5001 |date=2013-08-07 |issue=NCAP305I-KAR-13-054 |page=A-13 |url=http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/database/aspx/searchmedia2.aspx?mediatype=r&LJC=8309&existphoto=Y&p_tstno=8309&existreport=Y&r_tstno=8309&existvideo=Y&v_tstno=8309&database=v&tstno=8309 |accessdate=2014-02-20 |publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation, National Highway Safety Adminitstration |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226120230/http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/database/aspx/searchmedia2.aspx?mediatype=r&LJC=8309&existphoto=Y&p_tstno=8309&existreport=Y&r_tstno=8309&existvideo=Y&v_tstno=8309&database=v&tstno=8309 |archivedate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref name=NYT062312>{{cite news |url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/23/tesla-motors-launches-model-s-in-california/?ref=automobiles |title=Leaving Baggage On the Dock, a Flagship Departs From California |author=Josie Garthaite |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2012-06-23 |accessdate=2012-06-24}}</ref> {{asof|2012|06}} the battery pack uses modified [[Panasonic]] NCR18650A 3100[[Ampere-hour|mAh]] cells with nickel-cobalt-aluminum [[cathode]]s.<ref name=\"TMCharging\">{{cite web |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/models/charging#/highpower |title=Charge your Model S - Adapter Guide, High Power Charging, and Supercharge |publisher=Tesla Motors |accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref><ref name=USA062312>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2012/06/first-drive-teslas-model-s-electric-is-spectacular/1#.T-aCTdUV3nh |title=First Drive: Tesla's Model S electric is spectacular |author=Chris Woodyard |work=[[USA Today]] |date=2012-06-23 |accessdate=2012-06-24}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[commodity cell]]s, similar to those found in [[laptop]]s and [[mobile phone]]s, is in contrast to every other electric vehicle manufacturer who use specialized large format Li-Ion cells.<ref name=\"What Goes Into A Tesla Model S Battery--And What It May Cost\">{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Thomas |title=What Goes Into A Tesla Model S Battery--And What It May Cost |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1084682_what-goes-into-a-tesla-model-s-battery--and-what-it-may-cost |website=www.greencarreports.com |publisher=Green Car Reports |accessdate=2015-03-25}}</ref> The liquid-cooled battery pack uses an [[intumescent]] gel to aid in fireproofing and even heat distribution.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Body construction===\n\n====Aluminium coil blanking====\n98% of the Tesla Model S body is constructed from [[aluminium]]<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\">{{cite web |title=How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mzV7Y9B0tk |publisher=How Its Made |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> and is produced from between 50 and 60 separate coils of aluminium each for various components. The coils are unwound, flattened and cut in a blanking machine; additional cutting is also done using [[Laser cutting|laser cutter]]. The total weight of the aluminium used in the Model S is around\n{{convert|410|lb|kg}}.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\"/>\n\n====Tandem press lines====\n[[File:Stamp and Repeat (6858564222).jpg|thumb|left|Stacked side panels that have been formed on the tandem press line.]]\nA robot then transfers the aluminium blanks into the tandem press lines where the sheets are stamped into the various panels of the cars. The Schuler SMG hydraulic stamping press line is the largest in North America and the 6th largest in the world.<ref name=\"Can Tesla become a bigger company with Model S electric car? That's Elon Musk's gamble\"/> The presses use up to 11,000 [[ton-force]] to form the body panels; the upper section applies 1400 tonnes of downward force and the lower section 130 tonnes.<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> The blank aluminium sheet is stretched over the lower [[Die (manufacturing)|draw die]] and openings are cut with robots transferring the panels between processes. The workers then inspect each panel to ensure correct pressing.  The parts are then stacked in frames and stored. The machines press one part every 6 seconds and create 5,000 parts per day.<ref name=\"How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1\">{{cite web |title=How the Tesla Model S is Made , Tesla Motors Part 1 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_lfxPI5ObM |website=Wired.com |publisher=WIRED |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Drive unit installation===\nThe car is raised and the drive unit is installed into the rear [[axle]] assembly. The drive unit provides power directly to the [[wheel]]s without a [[drive shaft]].<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/>\n\n===Battery pack installation===\nThe [[battery pack]] weighs almost {{convert|1200|lb|kg}} and is delivered to the installation area and is raised into the car using a lift. Placing the battery pack under the cabin floor adds strength and rigidity to the car and lowers the vehicle's [[center of mass|center of gravity]]<ref name=\"How Its Made Dream Cars Season 02 Episode 10 Tesla Model S\"/> to {{convert|18|in|cm|abbr=out|0}}.<ref name=rope>{{cite web |first=L. David |last=Roper |url=http://www.roperld.com/science/TeslaModelS.htm |title=Tesla Model S Data |accessdate=2015-04-05 <!--sources at page bottom-->}}</ref><ref name=sciAbuild>{{cite journal |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-tesla-motors-builds-the-safest-car-video/ |title=How Tesla Motors Builds One of the World's Safest Cars [Video] |first=David |last=Biello |journal=Scientific American |date=2013-09-23 |access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> A [[titanium]] plate is installed over the battery pack which protects it in the event of a high-speed collision and to protect from road debris.<ref>{{cite web |last=George |first=Patrick |title=The Tesla Model S: Now With Road Debris-Crushing Titanium! |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-s-now-with-road-debris-crushing-titani-1553544362 |work=Jalopnik |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |accessdate=2014-03-31 |date=2014-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Blanco |first=Sebastian |title=Tesla adds free titanium underbody shields to Model S to prevent fires |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2014/03/28/prevent-fire-tesla-adds-free-titanium-underbody-shields-model-s/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330071458/http://green.autoblog.com/2014/03/28/prevent-fire-tesla-adds-free-titanium-underbody-shields-model-s/ |archive-date=2014-03-30 |work=Autoblog Green |publisher=[[AOL Inc.]] |accessdate=2014-03-31 |date=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Safety incidents==\nOn April 1, 2019, Tesla reached a settlement with the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) over its mishandling of hazardous waste in 2017. Tesla allowed hazardous waste to accumulate on site without a permit beyond the allowed 90 days; the EPA found Tesla failed to \"promptly clean up flammable paint and or solvent mixtures\", left two {{convert|55|USgal|L|adj=on}} containers of hazardous waste open with \"no gasket or locking mechanism\", and violated air emission standards for three leaky transmission lines that the waste moved through.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/404019872/Tesla-EPA-settlement-for-hazardous-materials-violation |title=Tesla / EPA settlement for hazardous materials violation {{!}} Resource Conservation And Recovery Act {{!}} Hazardous Waste|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013 there was an accident when the low-pressure aluminum casting press failed, spilling molten metal on three workers and causing their clothing to catch fire. Tesla was fined {{USD}}89,000 by the [[California Department of Industrial Relations|California Division of Occupational Safety and Health]] for seven safety violations, six considered serious.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla Motors faces $89,000 in fines for incident that injured workers at Fremont facility |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_25677719/tesla-motors-faces-fines-factory-violations-fremont |website=San Jose Mercury News |accessdate=2014-12-31 |date=2014-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Giga Nevada]]\n* [[Giga New York]]\n* [[Giga Shanghai]]\n* [[Giga Berlin]]\n* [[Tesla facilities in Tilburg]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*[http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/tesla-factory-birthplace-model-s The Tesla Factory: Birthplace of the Model S] Tesla Motors photo tour\n*[https://vimeo.com/43015249 Stamping], [https://vimeo.com/43083157 body], [https://vimeo.com/43505225 paint], [https://vimeo.com/109168998 automated motor production], [https://vimeo.com/43997600 assembly], [https://vimeo.com/106564929 factory upgrade] (official Tesla)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_lfxPI5ObM How Tesla Builds Electric Cars], A 3-part documentary on the Tesla Factory from [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'' magazine]]\n*[http://www.natgeotv.com/ca/megafactories/videos/brand-new-tesla-factory \"Brand New Tesla Factory\"], [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] video; {{youtube|kbusZ_iaUyE|Documentary}} by [[National Geographic Channel]] [[Ultimate Factories#Season 6 (2013)|Megafactories]]\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/403/nummi  NPR's This American Life's full hour story of the creation and demise of NUMMI - episode #403 ] from [[This American Life]]\n\n{{Tesla Motors}}\n\n{{coord|37|29|41.12|N|121|56|41.16|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Tesla factories]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle assembly plants in California]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Fremont, California]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established  in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesla_Factory"}
{"title_page": "CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe", "text_new": "{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=March 2018}}\n'''CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe''' (also known as CEJI)<ref>Yardley, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/24/world/europe/europes-anti-semitism-comes-out-of-shadows.html \"Europe\u2019s Anti-Semitism Comes Out of the Shadows\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Saracelles, 23 September 2014. Retrieved on 1 May 2019.</ref> is a [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGO) based in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]. Established in 1991, the organisation's areas of expertise include: education; inclusion and social cohesion; discrimination and xenophobia; hate speech and hate crime; media and digital literacy.<ref>https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/what-we-do/networks/radicalisation_awareness_network/civil-society-empowerment-programme/csep_db-467_en</ref>. It also provides anti-discrimination training to teachers, social workers and others.<ref>Yardley, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/24/world/europe/europes-anti-semitism-comes-out-of-shadows.html \"Europe\u2019s Anti-Semitism Comes Out of the Shadows\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Saracelles, 23 September 2014. Retrieved on 1 May 2019.</ref> The organisation recently launched a series of online courses ('Facing Facts') on hate crimes with support from [[Google]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] that provide 'tools to educators, activists and other professionals to identify and combat hate speech'. <ref>JTA. [https://www.timesofisrael.com/eu-can-fight-anti-semitism-without-defining-it-official-says \"EU can fight anti-Semitism without defining it, official says\"], ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', Brussels, 9 December 2016. Retrieved on 13 May 2019.</ref>\n\n== Current work ==\n=== Diversity Education ===\nCEJI has created education and training programmes, the aim of which is to \"enhance appreciation of Europe\u2019s diversity including Jews, Roma, Muslims, gays and lesbians, etc.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe|url=http://www.ceji.org/sites/default/files/publications/CEJI%2B-%2BA%2BJewish%2BContribution%2Bto%2Ban%2BInclusive%2BEurope-1.pdf}}</ref>\nThe current training programmes offered by CEJI, in a partnership entitled 'Belieforama', include: \n* Religious Diversity and Anti-Discrimination - foundation programme.\n* Overcoming [[Antisemitism]]\n* Overcoming [[Islamophobia]]\n* Reconciling [[Religion]], [[Gender]] and [[Sexual Orientation]]\n* Confronting [[Discrimination]]: Facilitation Skills\n* Confronting Discrimination: Taking Action\n\n=== Engaging Jewish Communities ===\nIn addition to its Overcoming Antisemitism programme, CEJI also runs a series of programmes specifically for the Jewish community:\n* ''Facing Facts!'' aims to improve monitoring and recording of hate crimes throughout the European Union. The project standardizes criteria for comparable hate crime data collection and works to train civil society organisations to gather, analyze and report incidents of hate crime and hate speech, be they anti-Jewish, anti-Roma, anti-homosexual or other.\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nCEJI's aim is to contribute to policy-making processes dealing with antisemitism, [[racism]], [[xenophobia]], discrimination and diversity education at the institutions of the European Union, the OSCE, the Council of Europe and within the wider spectrum of European organisations and networks active in these areas.\n\nRelated to this advocacy work is Facing Facts!, a project to improve monitoring and recording of hate crimes throughout the European Union by standardising criteria for comparable hate crime data collection. CEJI trains civil society organisations to gather, analyze and report incidents of hate crime and hate speech, be they anti-Jewish, anti-Roma, anti-homosexual or other.\n\n=== Intercultural Dialogue ===\nInterfaith and intercultural dialogue are key aspects of CEJI's work. According to CEJI: \"the dialogue approach is particularly pertinent to relations between Muslim and Jewish communities, which have been greatly affected by the volatile political climate of recent years\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://ceji.org/content/intercultural-dialogue |title=CEJI website}}</ref> CEJI offers training courses in both 'Overcoming Antisemitism' and 'Overcoming Islamophobia', often run as a combined training course.\n\n== Structure ==\n\n=== Staff members ===\nStaff members include director of CEJI Robin Sclafani, ''Facing Facts'' coordinator Melissa Sonnino, training coordinator St\u00e9phanie Lecesne, communication officer & hate speech advisor Julia Mozer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Board members ===\nBoard members of CEJI include Baron Alain Philippson of Marie and Alain Philippson Foundation, president of the Evens Foundation Corinne Evens, director of the Centrum Informatie en Documentatie Isra\u00ebl (Center for Information and Documentation Israel) (CIDI) Ronny Naftaniel, founding Chair of the Universal Education Foundation (UEF) Daniel Kropf, creator of Paris based consulting firm Weisblatt & associ\u00e9s Karen Weisblatt, associate of global law firm [[Sidley Austin|Sidley]] Yohan Benizri. Other board members include linguist [[Baron Julien Klener|Julien Klener]], head of Concept & Research (CORE) Lucyna Gutman-Grauer, Managing Director of the investment division of a Chinese industrial company Frederick Mocatta, International Director of Interreligious Affairs of [[American Jewish Committee|AJC]] [[David Rosen (rabbi)|Rabbi David Rosen]], and independent consultant and previous [[ADL]] Israel Office director Harry Wall.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Partnerships ==\nCEJI partnership and membership organizations. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Partner organizations ===\n\n* [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]]\n* [[Anti-Defamation League]] \u2013 United States\n* Association pour la R\u00e9novation des Etablissements Scolaires (ARES) \u2013 France\n* BMW Responsible Leaders Network\n* [[B'nai B'rith|B\u2019nai B\u2019rith]] Europe\n* [[Campaign Against Homophobia]] (KPH) \u2013 Poland\n* Center for Independent Journalism (CIJ)\n* Centre Bruxellois d\u2019Action Interculturelle (CBAI) \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre Communautaire La\u00efc Juif \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre pour l\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9 des chances et la lutte contre le racisme \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre R\u00e9gional de Verviers pour l\u2019Int\u00e9gration\n* Churches\u2019 Commission for Migrants in Europe\n* CIDI \u2013 Dutch Centre for Documentation and Information on Israel (The Netherlands)\n* COC \u2013 Federation of Dutch Associations for the Integration of Homosexuality (The Netherlands)\n* CST London \u2013 The Community Security Trust (UK)\n* Dispositif de concertation et d\u2019appui aux Centres R\u00e9gionaux d\u2019Int\u00e9gration (DISCRI)\n* Eine Welt der Vielfalt \u2013 Germany\n* European Muslim Initiative for Social Cohesion (EMISCO)\n* European Association for Jewish Culture\n* European Council of Jewish Communities\n* [[European Network Against Racism]] (ENAR)\n* ENAR Ireland\n* European Jewish Community Center (EJCC)\n* European Network on Independent Living (ENIL)\n* European Network on Religion and Belief (ENORB)\n* European Peer Training Organisation (EPTO)\n* European Platform on Religious Intolerance and Discrimination (EPRID)\n* [[European Roma Information Office]]\n* [[European Roma Rights Centre]]\n* European Social Platform\n* European Union of Jewish Students (EUJS)\n* Fonds Maribel \u2013 Belgium\n* Generation\n* The Grail\n* Haut Ecole de la Communaut\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise en Hainaut \u2013 Belgium\n* Haver Informal Jewish Educational Public Benefit Foundation; Hungary\n* [[ILGA-Europe|ILGA Europe]]\n* Institut for Criminal Policy Research (ICPR)\n* Instituto de Asuntos Culturales, Spain\n* Interfederal Centre for Equal Opportunities (UNIA) \u2013 Belgium\n* International Center for Journalists (ICFJ)\n* International Council of Jewish Women\n* The International League against Racism and Anti-Semitism / Ligue Internationale Contre le Racisme et l\u2019Antis\u00e9mitisme (LICRA)\n* International Lesbian and Gay Association (mo) Europe\n* Inter-parliamentary Coalition for Combating Antisemitism (ICCA)\n* Institute of Cultural Affairs (ICA)\n* Institutul Intercultural Timisoara\n* Justice 21 Association\n* La Ligue de l\u2019enseignement du Calvados \u2013 France\n* Learning for Wellbeing Foundation\n* Magenta Foundation \u2013 The Netherlands\n* Mazsihisz\n* [[Media Diversity Institute]] (MDI)\n* Minyanim\n* Movimiento Contra Intolerancia\n* Multi-Faith Centre, University of Derby \u2013 UK\n*[[National Police Chiefs' Council|National Police Chiefs\u2019 Council]]\n* Nordic Jewish Security Council\n* National University of Public Service \u2013 Hungary\n* Osservatorio per la sicurezza contro gli atti discriminatori \u2013 OSCAD\n* Partners Bulgaria Foundation \u2013 Bulgaria\n* Praksis \u2013 Greece\n* Symbiosis\n* Terez\u00edn Initiative Institute\n* [[World Congress of Imams and Rabbis for Peace]]\n\n=== CEJI memberships ===\n\n* [[European Network Against Racism]] (ENAR)\n* European Network on Religion and Belief (ENORB)\n* European Peer Training Organisation (EPTO)\n* European Platform on Religious Intolerance and Discrimination (EPRID)\n* International Network Against Cyber Hate\n\n=== Funders ===\n\n* Baron Alain Philippson\n* [[Anna Lindh Euro-Mediterranean Foundation for the Dialogue Between Cultures|Anna Lindh Euro - Mediterranean Foundation for the Dialogue between Cultures]]\n* Association Verbe et Lumi\u00e8re-Vigilance\n* Bernheim Foundation\n* Charles Leopold Mayer Foundation\n* Compagnia di San Paolo\n* Communaut\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise de Belgique FIPI (Fonds d\u2019Impulsion \u00e0 la politique des immigr\u00e9s)\n* Dutch Jewish Humanitarian Fund\n* [[Edmond de Rothschild Foundation|The Edmond de Rothschild Foundations]]\n* [[European Cultural Foundation]]\n* European Youth Foundation\n* Evens Foundation\n* [[Facebook]]\n* Fondation Marie & Alain Philippson\n* Fonds Maribel \u2013 Belgium\n* [[Ford Foundation]]\n* [[Google]]\n* [[King Baudouin Foundation]]\n* Levi Strauss Foundation\n* [[Open Society Foundations]]\n*[[Pears Foundation]]\n* The Rothschild Foundation Europe\n* [[Twitter]]\n\n== Publications ==\n* [http://ceji.org/content/facing-facts-hate-crime-monitoring-guidelines Facing Facts! Hate Crime Monitoring Guidelines]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150913181838/http://www.ceji.org/content/learning-experience-leading-engagement-full-policy-document Learning from Experience, Leading to Engagement Policy Document] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150914040422/http://www.ceji.org/content/citizenship-education-diversity-guidelines-considerations-policy-makers-and-practitioners Citizenship Education for Diversity: Guidelines & Considerations for Policy Makers and Practitioners]\n\n==Awards==\n* Gold Prize European Awards for Lifelong Learning programme, 2008 (under former name 'Centre Europ\u00e9en Juif d'Information').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-08-929_en.htm |title=European Commission website}}</ref>\n* BMW Group's First Prize for Intercultural Commitment<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weller |first1=Paul |last2= |first2= |date=2017 |title=Learning from experience, leading to engagement: Lessons from Belieforama for a Europe of religion and belief diversity |url=https://pureportal.coventry.ac.uk/en/publications/learning-from-experience-leading-to-engagement-lessons-from-belie |journal=Studies in Interreligious Dialogue |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=1 |doi=10.2143/SID.27.2.3269034 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ceji.org CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe website]\n* [http://www.belieforama.eu Belieforama website]\n* [http://www.facingfacts.eu Facing Facts! website]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n[[Category:International organisations based in Belgium]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=March 2018}}\n'''CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe''' (also known as CEJI)<ref>Yardley, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/24/world/europe/europes-anti-semitism-comes-out-of-shadows.html \"Europe\u2019s Anti-Semitism Comes Out of the Shadows\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Saracelles, 23 September 2014. Retrieved on 1 May 2019.</ref> is a [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGO) based in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]. Established in 1991, the organisation's areas of expertise include: education; inclusion and social cohesion; discrimination and xenophobia; hate speech and hate crime; media and digital literacy.<ref>https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/what-we-do/networks/radicalisation_awareness_network/civil-society-empowerment-programme/csep_db-467_en</ref>. It also provides anti-discrimination training to teachers, social workers and others.<ref>Yardley, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/24/world/europe/europes-anti-semitism-comes-out-of-shadows.html \"Europe\u2019s Anti-Semitism Comes Out of the Shadows\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Saracelles, 23 September 2014. Retrieved on 1 May 2019.</ref> The organisation recently launched a series of online courses ('Facing Facts') on hate crimes with support from [[Google]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] that provide 'tools to educators, activists and other professionals to identify and combat hate speech'. <ref>JTA. [https://www.timesofisrael.com/eu-can-fight-anti-semitism-without-defining-it-official-says \"EU can fight anti-Semitism without defining it, official says\"], ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', Brussels, 9 December 2016. Retrieved on 13 May 2019.</ref>\n\n== Current work ==\n=== Diversity Education ===\nCEJI has created education and training programmes, the aim of which is to \"enhance appreciation of Europe\u2019s diversity including Jews, Roma, Muslims, gays and lesbians, etc.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe|url=http://www.ceji.org/sites/default/files/publications/CEJI%2B-%2BA%2BJewish%2BContribution%2Bto%2Ban%2BInclusive%2BEurope-1.pdf}}</ref>\nThe current training programmes offered by CEJI, in a partnership entitled 'Belieforama', include: \n* Religious Diversity and Anti-Discrimination - foundation programme.\n* Overcoming [[Antisemitism]]\n* Overcoming [[Islamophobia]]\n* Reconciling [[Religion]], [[Gender]] and [[Sexual Orientation]]\n* Confronting [[Discrimination]]: Facilitation Skills\n* Confronting Discrimination: Taking Action\n\n=== Engaging Jewish Communities ===\nIn addition to its Overcoming Antisemitism programme, CEJI also runs a series of programmes specifically for the Jewish community:\n* ''Facing Facts!'' aims to improve monitoring and recording of hate crimes throughout the European Union. The project standardizes criteria for comparable hate crime data collection and works to train civil society organisations to gather, analyze and report incidents of hate crime and hate speech, be they anti-Jewish, anti-Roma, anti-homosexual or other.\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nCEJI's aim is to contribute to policy-making processes dealing with antisemitism, [[racism]], [[xenophobia]], discrimination and diversity education at the institutions of the European Union, the OSCE, the Council of Europe and within the wider spectrum of European organisations and networks active in these areas.\n\nRelated to this advocacy work is Facing Facts!, a project to improve monitoring and recording of hate crimes throughout the European Union by standardising criteria for comparable hate crime data collection. CEJI trains civil society organisations to gather, analyze and report incidents of hate crime and hate speech, be they anti-Jewish, anti-Roma, anti-homosexual or other.\n\n=== Intercultural Dialogue ===\nInterfaith and intercultural dialogue are key aspects of CEJI's work. According to CEJI: \"the dialogue approach is particularly pertinent to relations between Muslim and Jewish communities, which have been greatly affected by the volatile political climate of recent years\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://ceji.org/content/intercultural-dialogue |title=CEJI website}}</ref> CEJI offers training courses in both 'Overcoming Antisemitism' and 'Overcoming Islamophobia', often run as a combined training course.\n\n== Structure ==\n\n=== Staff members ===\nStaff members include director of CEJI Robin Sclafani, Facing Facts Coordinator Melissa Sonnino, Training Coordinator St\u00e9phanie Lecesne, Communication Officer & Hate Speech Advisor Julia Mozer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Board members ===\nBoard members of CEJI include Baron Alain Philippson of Marie and Alain Philippson Foundation, President of the Evens Foundation Corinne Evens, director of the Centrum Informatie en Documentatie Isra\u00ebl (Center for Information and Documentation Israel) (CIDI) Ronny Naftaniel, Founding Chair of the Universal Education Foundation (UEF) Daniel Kropf, creator of Paris based consulting firm Weisblatt & associ\u00e9s Karen Weisblatt, associate of global law firm [[Sidley Austin|Sidley]] Yohan Benizri. Other board members include linguist [[Baron Julien Klener|Julien Klener]], head of Concept & Research (CORE) Lucyna Gutman-Grauer, Managing Director of the investment division of a Chinese industrial company Frederick Mocatta, International Director of Interreligious Affairs of [[American Jewish Committee|AJC]] [[David Rosen (rabbi)|Rabbi David Rosen]], and independent consultant and previous [[ADL]] Israel Office director Harry Wall.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Partnerships ==\nCEJI partnership and membership organizations. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Partner organizations ===\n\n* [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]]\n* [[Anti-Defamation League]] \u2013 United States\n* Association pour la R\u00e9novation des Etablissements Scolaires (ARES) \u2013 France\n* BMW Responsible Leaders Network\n* [[B'nai B'rith|B\u2019nai B\u2019rith]] Europe\n* [[Campaign Against Homophobia]] (KPH) \u2013 Poland\n* Center for Independent Journalism (CIJ)\n* Centre Bruxellois d\u2019Action Interculturelle (CBAI) \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre Communautaire La\u00efc Juif \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre pour l\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9 des chances et la lutte contre le racisme \u2013 Belgium\n* Centre R\u00e9gional de Verviers pour l\u2019Int\u00e9gration\n* Churches\u2019 Commission for Migrants in Europe\n* CIDI \u2013 Dutch Centre for Documentation and Information on Israel (The Netherlands)\n* COC \u2013 Federation of Dutch Associations for the Integration of Homosexuality (The Netherlands)\n* CST London \u2013 The Community Security Trust (UK)\n* Dispositif de concertation et d\u2019appui aux Centres R\u00e9gionaux d\u2019Int\u00e9gration (DISCRI)\n* Eine Welt der Vielfalt \u2013 Germany\n* European Muslim Initiative for Social Cohesion (EMISCO)\n* European Association for Jewish Culture\n* European Council of Jewish Communities\n* [[European Network Against Racism]] (ENAR)\n* ENAR Ireland\n* European Jewish Community Center (EJCC)\n* European Network on Independent Living (ENIL)\n* European Network on Religion and Belief (ENORB)\n* European Peer Training Organisation (EPTO)\n* European Platform on Religious Intolerance and Discrimination (EPRID)\n* [[European Roma Information Office]]\n* [[European Roma Rights Centre]]\n* European Social Platform\n* European Union of Jewish Students (EUJS)\n* Fonds Maribel \u2013 Belgium\n* Generation\n* The Grail\n* Haut Ecole de la Communaut\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise en Hainaut \u2013 Belgium\n* Haver Informal Jewish Educational Public Benefit Foundation; Hungary\n* [[ILGA-Europe|ILGA Europe]]\n* Institut for Criminal Policy Research (ICPR)\n* Instituto de Asuntos Culturales, Spain\n* Interfederal Centre for Equal Opportunities (UNIA) \u2013 Belgium\n* International Center for Journalists (ICFJ)\n* International Council of Jewish Women\n* The International League against Racism and Anti-Semitism / Ligue Internationale Contre le Racisme et l\u2019Antis\u00e9mitisme (LICRA)\n* International Lesbian and Gay Association (mo) Europe\n* Inter-parliamentary Coalition for Combating Antisemitism (ICCA)\n* Institute of Cultural Affairs (ICA)\n* Institutul Intercultural Timisoara\n* Justice 21 Association\n* La Ligue de l\u2019enseignement du Calvados \u2013 France\n* Learning for Wellbeing Foundation\n* Magenta Foundation \u2013 The Netherlands\n* Mazsihisz\n* [[Media Diversity Institute]] (MDI)\n* Minyanim\n* Movimiento Contra Intolerancia\n* Multi-Faith Centre, University of Derby \u2013 UK\n*[[National Police Chiefs' Council|National Police Chiefs\u2019 Council]]\n* Nordic Jewish Security Council\n* National University of Public Service \u2013 Hungary\n* Osservatorio per la sicurezza contro gli atti discriminatori \u2013 OSCAD\n* Partners Bulgaria Foundation \u2013 Bulgaria\n* Praksis \u2013 Greece\n* Symbiosis\n* Terez\u00edn Initiative Institute\n* [[World Congress of Imams and Rabbis for Peace]]\n\n=== CEJI memberships ===\n\n* [[European Network Against Racism]] (ENAR)\n* European Network on Religion and Belief (ENORB)\n* European Peer Training Organisation (EPTO)\n* European Platform on Religious Intolerance and Discrimination (EPRID)\n* International Network Against Cyber Hate\n\n=== Funders ===\n\n* Baron Alain Philippson\n* [[Anna Lindh Euro-Mediterranean Foundation for the Dialogue Between Cultures|Anna Lindh Euro - Mediterranean Foundation for the Dialogue between Cultures]]\n* Association Verbe et Lumi\u00e8re-Vigilance\n* Bernheim Foundation\n* Charles Leopold Mayer Foundation\n* Compagnia di San Paolo\n* Communaut\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise de Belgique FIPI (Fonds d\u2019Impulsion \u00e0 la politique des immigr\u00e9s)\n* Dutch Jewish Humanitarian Fund\n* [[Edmond de Rothschild Foundation|The Edmond de Rothschild Foundations]]\n* [[European Cultural Foundation]]\n* European Youth Foundation\n* Evens Foundation\n* [[Facebook]]\n* Fondation Marie & Alain Philippson\n* Fonds Maribel \u2013 Belgium\n* [[Ford Foundation]]\n* [[Google]]\n* [[King Baudouin Foundation]]\n* Levi Strauss Foundation\n* [[Open Society Foundations]]\n*[[Pears Foundation]]\n* The Rothschild Foundation Europe\n* [[Twitter]]\n\n== Publications ==\n* [http://ceji.org/content/facing-facts-hate-crime-monitoring-guidelines Facing Facts! Hate Crime Monitoring Guidelines]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150913181838/http://www.ceji.org/content/learning-experience-leading-engagement-full-policy-document Learning from Experience, Leading to Engagement Policy Document] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150914040422/http://www.ceji.org/content/citizenship-education-diversity-guidelines-considerations-policy-makers-and-practitioners Citizenship Education for Diversity: Guidelines & Considerations for Policy Makers and Practitioners]\n\n==Awards==\n* Gold Prize European Awards for Lifelong Learning programme, 2008 (under former name 'Centre Europ\u00e9en Juif d'Information').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-08-929_en.htm |title=European Commission website}}</ref>\n* BMW Group's First Prize for Intercultural Commitment<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weller |first1=Paul |last2= |first2= |date=2017 |title=Learning from experience, leading to engagement: Lessons from Belieforama for a Europe of religion and belief diversity |url=https://pureportal.coventry.ac.uk/en/publications/learning-from-experience-leading-to-engagement-lessons-from-belie |journal=Studies in Interreligious Dialogue |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=1 |doi=10.2143/SID.27.2.3269034 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ceji.org CEJI - A Jewish Contribution to an Inclusive Europe website]\n* [http://www.belieforama.eu Belieforama website]\n* [http://www.facingfacts.eu Facing Facts! website]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n[[Category:International organisations based in Belgium]]\n", "name_user": "YitzhakNat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStaff members", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CEJI_-_A_Jewish_Contribution_to_an_Inclusive_Europe"}
{"title_page": "Wayne Carlisle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Wayne Carlisle\n| image               =\n| fullname            = Wayne Thomas Carlisle\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1979|9|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lisburn]], Northern Ireland\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132002 | clubs1 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]      | caps1 = 46 | goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan) | caps2 = 11 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]      | caps3 = 71 | goals3 = 14\n| years4 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]        | caps4 = 40 | goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 2006\u20132008 | clubs5 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]            | caps5 = 62 | goals5 = 10\n| years7 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs7 = [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]      | caps7 = 71 | goals7 = 10\n| years8 = 2011    | clubs8 = [[Truro City F.C.|Truro City]]              | caps8 = 3  | goals8 = 0\n|totalcaps = 304 | totalgoals = 42\n| club-update         =\n| nationalyears1 = 1999\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland U21 & B]] | nationalcaps1 = 12| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Wayne Thomas Carlisle''' (born 9 September 1979 in [[Lisburn]], Northern Ireland) is a former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who last played for [[Football League Two]] side [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]].\n\nCarlisle was a [[midfielder]] during his playing career, primarily right-sided, but able to play in a wide range of positions. He has been [[Cap (sport)|capped]] by [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] at youth, under-21 level and B international.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/1365188.stm|title=Wayne shows true grit|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 June 2001|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nCarlisle is currently assistant manager at [[Exeter City F.C.]] having been appointed in 2019.\n\n==Career==\nHe began his career with then English [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Due to the club's financial troubles during the late 1990s, first-team opportunities became available for the then-young trainee. He made his league debut in February 1999 in Palace's 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=255956|title= C Palace 1-1 Birmingham|publisher=Soccerbase|date=6 February 1999|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> Carlisle featured in 46 first team league matches while at [[Selhurst Park]], but when [[Simon Jordan]] stepped in to save the club, investments in more experienced and high-profile players limited Carlisle's chances.\n\nIn October 2001 Carlisle moved on loan to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] for three months, where he featured in 11 matches, scoring 2 goals. On 28 March 2002, Carlisle moved on a free transfer to [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/1899331.stm|title=Rovers snap up duo|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=28 March 2002|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> In his over two years at [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]], Carlisle produced a scoring record of 14 goals in 71 matches, this despite the team struggling against relegation. With Rovers needing to cut costs, Carlisle, along with teammate [[Danny Boxall]] was placed on the transfer list in December 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/3319731.stm|title=Rovers release Still|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=2009-01-07|date=15 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nHe was released by Rovers in May 2004<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/3707451.stm|title=Atkins begins clearout|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 May 2004|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> and joined then [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] on a two-year contract the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leyton_orient/3876565.stm|title=Orient capture Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 July 2004|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> In the [[2005-06 in English football|2005-06]] season, Carlisle was restricted to mostly appearances from the bench, and transferred to [[Conference National]] side [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] in the January [[transfer window]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/4620658.stm|title=Exeter swoop for winger Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=17 January 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nCarlisle started promisingly with his new club, breaking straight into the first team, but his season was ended prematurely with a broken leg suffered against [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/4861000.stm|title=Exeter winger Carlisle breaks leg|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=30 March 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> At the end of the season, departing manager [[Alex Inglethorpe]] released Carlisle on a free transfer.\n\nOn 6 October 2006 Carlisle was re-signed by new [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] manager [[Paul Tisdale]] after impressing as an early season trialist. Carlisle was taken to hospital on 19 October 2006 to have his [[Vermiform appendix|appendix]] removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/6128320.stm|title=Carlisle return to boost Exeter|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 November 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> He broke back into the Exeter City first team, was offered an extended contract,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/6240815.stm|title=Grecians offer Carlisle new deal|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 January 2007|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> and was involved in their [[Conference National Playoff Final 2008|promotion]] to [[the Football League]] in 2008, scoring in both of the play-off semi-final games against local rivals [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]].\n\nAlthough offered a contract by Exeter, Carlisle chose to join Torquay United in May 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/torquay_united/7425589.stm|title=Gulls sign Exeter winger Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 May 2008|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> where on his third visit to the new Wembley in three years Carlisle gained his 2nd consecutive promotion. Carlisle started the 2009\u201310 season in fine form but early in the new year sustained a knee injury which restricted him to on a handful of games before the end of the season. Carlisle signed a six-month contract with Torquay United at the start of the 2010\u201311 season but in January 2011 took the decision to retire from professional football to pursue a career in player development at Ivybridge Community College, Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ivybridge.devon.sch.uk/index.phtml?d=563400|title=Ivybridge Community College|last=|first=|date=|website=ivybridge.devon.sch.uk|publisher=|access-date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\nOn 4 March 2011, Carlisle signed for Southern Premier League side [[Truro City F.C.|Truro City]] but his spell there was short lived and in May 2011 he retired from  playing football altogether to focus on a career in coaching.\n\nCarlisle is now Assistant Manager at former club [[Exeter City F.C.]], having been appointed in July 2019 after the departure of Eric Kinder.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlisle, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association footballers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leyton Orient F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Torquay United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Truro City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lisburn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Wayne Carlisle\n| image               =\n| fullname            = Wayne Thomas Carlisle\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1979|9|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lisburn]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| height              = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub         =\n| clubnumber          =\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132002 | clubs1 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]      | caps1 = 46 | goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan) | caps2 = 11 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]      | caps3 = 71 | goals3 = 14\n| years4 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]        | caps4 = 40 | goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 2006\u20132008 | clubs5 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]            | caps5 = 62 | goals5 = 10\n| years7 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs7 = [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]      | caps7 = 71 | goals7 = 10\n| years8 = 2011    | clubs8 = [[Truro City F.C.|Truro City]]              | caps8 = 3  | goals8 = 0\n|totalcaps = 304 | totalgoals = 42\n| club-update         =\n| nationalyears1 = 1999\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland U21 & B]] | nationalcaps1 = 12| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Wayne Thomas Carlisle''' (born 9 September 1979 in [[Lisburn]], [[Northern Ireland]]) is a former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who last played for [[Football League Two]] side [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]].\n\nCarlisle was a [[midfielder]] during his playing career, primarily right-sided, but able to play in a wide range of positions. He has been [[Cap (sport)|capped]] by [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] at youth, under-21 level and B international.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/1365188.stm|title=Wayne shows true grit|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 June 2001|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nCarlisle is currently assistant manager at [[Exeter City F.C.]] having been appointed in 2019.\n\n==Career==\nHe began his career with then English [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Due to the club's financial troubles during the late 1990s, first-team opportunities became available for the then-young trainee. He made his league debut in February 1999 in Palace's 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=255956|title= C Palace 1-1 Birmingham|publisher=Soccerbase|date=6 February 1999|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> Carlisle featured in 46 first team league matches while at [[Selhurst Park]], but when [[Simon Jordan]] stepped in to save the club, investments in more experienced and high-profile players limited Carlisle's chances.\n\nIn October 2001 Carlisle moved on loan to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] for three months, where he featured in 11 matches, scoring 2 goals. On 28 March 2002, Carlisle moved on a free transfer to [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/1899331.stm|title=Rovers snap up duo|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=28 March 2002|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> In his over two years at [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]], Carlisle produced a scoring record of 14 goals in 71 matches, this despite the team struggling against relegation. With Rovers needing to cut costs, Carlisle, along with teammate [[Danny Boxall]] was placed on the transfer list in December 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/3319731.stm|title=Rovers release Still|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=2009-01-07|date=15 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nHe was released by Rovers in May 2004<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/3707451.stm|title=Atkins begins clearout|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 May 2004|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> and joined then [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] on a two-year contract the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leyton_orient/3876565.stm|title=Orient capture Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 July 2004|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> In the [[2005-06 in English football|2005-06]] season, Carlisle was restricted to mostly appearances from the bench, and transferred to [[Conference National]] side [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] in the January [[transfer window]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/4620658.stm|title=Exeter swoop for winger Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=17 January 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nCarlisle started promisingly with his new club, breaking straight into the first team, but his season was ended prematurely with a broken leg suffered against [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/4861000.stm|title=Exeter winger Carlisle breaks leg|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=30 March 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> At the end of the season, departing manager [[Alex Inglethorpe]] released Carlisle on a free transfer.\n\nOn 6 October 2006 Carlisle was re-signed by new [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] manager [[Paul Tisdale]] after impressing as an early season trialist. Carlisle was taken to hospital on 19 October 2006 to have his [[Vermiform appendix|appendix]] removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/6128320.stm|title=Carlisle return to boost Exeter|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 November 2006|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>  He broke back into the Exeter City first team, was offered an extended contract,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/6240815.stm|title=Grecians offer Carlisle new deal|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=8 January 2007|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> and was involved in their [[Conference National Playoff Final 2008|promotion]] to [[the Football League]] in 2008, scoring in both of the play-off semi-final games against local rivals [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]].\n\nAlthough offered a contract by Exeter, Carlisle chose to join Torquay United in May 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/torquay_united/7425589.stm|title=Gulls sign Exeter winger Carlisle|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 May 2008|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> where on his third visit to the new Wembley in three years Carlisle gained his 2nd consecutive promotion. Carlisle started the 2009\u201310 season in fine form but early in the new year sustained a knee injury which restricted him to on a handful of games before the end of the season. Carlisle signed a six-month contract with Torquay United at the start of the 2010-11 season but in January 2011 took the decision to retire from professional football to pursue a career in player development at Ivybridge Community College, Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ivybridge.devon.sch.uk/index.phtml?d=563400|title=Ivybridge Community College|last=|first=|date=|website=ivybridge.devon.sch.uk|publisher=|access-date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\nOn 4 March 2011, Carlisle signed for Southern Premier League side [[Truro City F.C.|Truro City]] but his spell there was short lived and in May 2011 he retired from  playing football altogether to focus on a career in coaching.\n\nCarlisle is now Assistant Manager at former club [[Exeter City F.C.]], having been appointed in July 2019 after the departure of Eric Kinder.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlisle, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association footballers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leyton Orient F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Torquay United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Truro City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lisburn]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, remove unref height,typo(s) fixed: 2010-11 \u2192 2010\u201311", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayne_Carlisle"}
{"title_page": "Transplastomic plant", "text_new": "<!--EDIT BELOW THIS LINE-->[[File:Plastids_types_en.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plastids_types_en.svg|thumb|283x283px|Plastid Examples]]\nA '''transplastomic plant''' is a [[genetically modified plant]] in which [[gene]]s are inactivated, modified or new foreign genes are inserted into the [[DNA]] of [[plastid]]s like the [[chloroplast]] instead of nuclear DNA.\n\nCurrently, the majority of transplastomic plants are as a result of chloroplast manipulation due to poor expression in other [[plastids]].<ref name=\":032\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Rigano MM, Scotti N, Cardi T|date=2012-11-24|title=Unsolved problems in plastid transformation|journal=Bioengineered|volume=3|issue=6|pages=329\u201333|doi=10.4161/bioe.21452|pmc=3489708|pmid=22892591}}</ref>\n\nChloroplasts in plants are thought to have originated from an engulfing event of a photosynthetic bacteria ([[Cyanobacteria|cyanobacterial ancestor)]] by a eukaroyte.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Raven JA, Allen JF|date=2003|title=Genomics and chloroplast evolution: what did cyanobacteria do for plants?|journal=Genome Biology|volume=4|issue=3|pages=209|doi=10.1186/gb-2003-4-3-209|pmc=153454|pmid=12620099}}</ref> There are many advantageous in chloroplast DNA manipulation because of its bacterial origin. For example, the ability to introduce [[Operon|multiple genes]] (operons) in a single step instead of many steps and the simultaneous expression of many genes with its bacterial gene expression system.<ref name=\":22222\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Adem M, Beyene D, Feyissa T|date=2017-04-01|title=Recent achievements obtained by chloroplast transformation|journal=Plant Methods|volume=13|issue=1|pages=30|doi=10.1186/s13007-017-0179-1|pmc=5395794|pmid=28428810}}</ref> Other advantageous include, the ability to obtain organic products like [[protein]]s at a high concentrations and the fact that production of these products will not be affected by [[Epigenetics|epigenetic regulation]].<ref name=\":132\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ahmad N, Michoux F, L\u00f6ssl AG, Nixon PJ|date=November 2016|title=Challenges and perspectives in commercializing plastid transformation technology|url=https://academic.oup.com/jxb/article/67/21/5945/2738940|journal=Journal of Experimental Botany|volume=67|issue=21|pages=5945\u20135960|doi=10.1093/jxb/erw360|pmid=27697788}}</ref> The reason for product synthesis at high concentrations is because a single plant cell can potentially carry up to a 100 chloroplast (like in ''Arabidopsis''), which if all transformed can express the introduced foreign [[Gene|genes)]], compared to transformation of the nucleus which can only express [[Copy-number variation|one copy of the gene]].<ref name=\":032\" />\n\nThe advantageous provided by chloroplast DNA manipulation has seen growing interest into this field of research and development, particularly in agricultural and pharmaceutical applications.<ref name=\":132\" /> However, there are some disadvantageous in chloroplast DNA manipulation, such as the inability to manipulate [[Cereal|cereal crops]] DNA material and poor expression of foreign DNA in non- green plastids as mentioned before.<ref name=\":132\" /> Nevertheless, much progress has been made into plant transplatomics, for example, the production of edible vaccines for [[Tetanus]] by using a transplastomic [[Nicotiana|tobacco]] plant.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Tregoning J, Maliga P, Dougan G, Nixon PJ|date=April 2004|title=New advances in the production of edible plant vaccines: chloroplast expression of a tetanus vaccine antigen, TetC|journal=Phytochemistry|volume=65|issue=8|pages=989\u201394|doi=10.1016/j.phytochem.2004.03.004|pmid=15110679}}</ref>\n\n== Transformation and selection procedure ==\n=== Gene construct ===\n[[File:Plant_Gene_Cassette_Schematic_for_Plant_Transplastomics.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plant_Gene_Cassette_Schematic_for_Plant_Transplastomics.jpg|thumb|325x325px|Plant Gene Cassette Schematic for Plant Transplastomics]]\nThe first requirement for transplastomic plant generation is to have a suitable [[Gene cassette|gene construct]] that can be introduced into a plastid like a chloroplast in the form of an ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' [[plasmid]] vector.<ref name=\":0222\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurekaselect.com/72509/article|title=Plant Plastid Engineering|last=Wani|first=Shabir H.|last2=Haider|first2=Nadia|date=2010-10-31|website=Current Genomics|language=en|doi=10.2174/138920210793175912|pmc=3048312|pmid=21532834|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Singh|first3=Hitesh Kumar and N. B.}}</ref> There are several key features of a suitable gene cassette including but not limited to ('''1''') [[selectable marker]] ('''2''') flanking sequences ('''3''') gene of interest ('''4''') [[Promoter (genetics)|promoter sequences]] ('''5''') [[5' UTR]] ('''6''') [[3'-UTR|3' UTR]] ('''7''') [[Intergenic region|intercistronic elements]].<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Verma D, Daniell H|date=December 2007|title=Chloroplast vector systems for biotechnology applications|journal=Plant Physiology|volume=145|issue=4|pages=1129\u201343|doi=10.1104/pp.107.106690|pmc=2151729|pmid=18056863}}</ref> The selectable marker typically tends to be an antiobiotic resistant gene, which would give the plant cell the ability to tolerate being grown on antibiotic containing agar plates.<ref name=\":132\" /> Flanking sequences are crucial for introduction of the gene construct at precised determined points of the plastid genome through [[homologous recombination]].<ref name=\":22222\"/> The gene of interests introduced have many different applications and can range from pest resistance genes to vaccine antigen production.<ref name=\":22222\" /> Intercistronic elements (IEE) are important for facilitating high levels of gene expression if multiple genes are introduced in the form of an [[operon]].<ref name=\":22222\" /> Finally, the 5' UTR and 3' UTR enhances ribosomal binding and increases transcript stability respectively.<ref name=\":22222\" />\n\n=== Transformation and selection ===\nThe most common method for plastid tranformation is [[Gene gun|biolistics]]: Small gold or tungsten particles are coated with the plasmid vector and shot into young plant cells or plant embryos, penetrating multiple cell layers and into the plastid.<ref name=\":0222\" /> There will then be a homologous recombination event between the shot plasmid vector and the [[Genome|plastid's genome]], hopefully resulting in a stable insertion of the gene cassette into the plastid.<ref name=\":0222\" /> Whilst the [[Transformation (genetics)|transformation]] efficiency is lower than in [[Agrobacterium tumefaciens|agrobacterial]] mediated transformation, which is also common in plant genetic engineering, particle bombardment is especially suitable for chloroplast transformation. Other transformation methods include the use of [[polyethylene glycol]] (PEG)- mediated transformation, which involves the removal of the plant [[cell wall]] in order to expose the [[Protoplast|\"naked\" plant cell]] to the foreign genetic material for transformation in the presence of PEG.<ref name=\":0222\" /> PEG- mediated transformation however, is notoriously time consuming, very technical and labor intensive as it requires the removal of the cell wall which is a key protective structural component of the plant cell.<ref name=\":1222\">{{Cite journal|last=Gan|first=Qinhua|last2=Jiang|first2=Jiaoyun|last3=Han|first3=Xiao|last4=Wang|first4=Shifan|last5=Lu|first5=Yandu|date=2018|title=Engineering the Chloroplast Genome of Oleaginous Marine Microalga Nannochloropsis oceanica|url=https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpls.2018.00439/full|journal=Frontiers in Plant Science|language=English|volume=9|doi=10.3389/fpls.2018.00439|issn=1664-462X|pmc=5904192|pmid=29696028}}</ref> Interestingly, a paper released in 2018 has described a successful plastid transformation of the chloroplast from the microalgae species ''[[Nannochloropsis|N. oceanica]]'' and ''[[Chlamydomonas reinhardtii|C. reinhardtii]]'' through [[electroporation]].<ref name=\":1222\" /> Whilst no study has been attempted yet for plastid transformation of [[higher plants]] using electroporation, this could be an interesting area of study for the future.\n\nIn order to persist and be stably maintained in the cell, a plasmid DNA molecule must contain an [[origin of replication]], which allows it to be replicated in the cell independently of the [[chromosome]]. When foreign DNA is first introduced to the plant tissue, not all chloroplasts will have successfully integrated the introduced genetic material.<ref name=\":132\" /> There will be a mixture of normal and transformed chloroplast within the plant cells. This mix of normal and transformed chloroplasts are defined to be \"[[Heteroplasmy|heteroplasmic]]\" chloroplast population.<ref name=\":132\" /> Stable gene expression of the introduced gene requires a \"[[Homoplasmy|homoplasmic]]\" population of transformed chloroplasts in the plant cells, where all the chloroplasts in the plant cell has successfully integrated the foreign genetic material.<ref name=\":132\" /> Typically, homoplasmicity can be achieved and identified through multiple rounds of selection on antibiotics.<ref name=\":132\" /> This is where the transformed plant tissue are grown repeatedly on agar plates that contain antibiotics like spectinomycin.<ref name=\":132\" /> Only plant cells that have successfully integrated the gene cassette as shown above will be able to express the antibiotic resistance selectable marker and therefore grow normally on agar plates containing antibiotics.<ref name=\":132\" /> Plant [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]] that do not grow normally will have a bleached appearance as the spectinomycin antibiotic [[Inhibitor|inhibits]] the [[ribosome]] of the plant cell<ref name=\":132\" /> However, as heteroplasmic population of chloroplasts may still be able to grow on agar plates effectively, many rounds of antibiotic selection and regrowth are required to cultivate a plant tissue that is homoplasmic and stable.<ref name=\":132\" /> Generation of homoplasmic plant tissue is considered to be a major difficulty and incredibly time consuming.<ref name=\":0222\" />\n\n== Biological containment and agricultural coexistence ==\n[[File:Nicotiana Tobacco Plants 1909px.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nicotiana%20Tobacco%20Plants%201909px.jpg|thumb|Nicotiana Tobacco Plant]]\nGenetically modified plants must be safe for the environment and suitable for [[Co-existence of genetically modified and conventional crops and derived food and feed|coexistence with conventional and organic crops]]. A major hurdle for traditional nuclear genetically modified crops is posed by the potential [[outcrossing]] of the [[transgene]] via pollen movement. Initially it was thought that, plastid transformation, which yields transplastomic plants in which the pollen does not contain the transgene, not only increases biosafety, but also facilitates the coexistence of genetically modified, conventional and organic agriculture. Therefore, developing such crops was a major goal of research projects such as [[Co-Extra]] and Transcontainer.\n\nHowever, a study conducted on the [[Nicotiana|tabacco plant]] in 2007 has disproved this theory. Led by Ralph Bock from the Max Planck Institute of Molecular Plant Physiology in Germany, researchers studied genetically modified tobacco in which the transgene was integrated in chloroplasts.<ref name=\":03222\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ruf S, Karcher D, Bock R|date=April 2007|title=Determining the transgene containment level provided by chloroplast transformation|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=104|issue=17|pages=6998\u20137002|doi=10.1073/pnas.0700008104|pmc=1849964|pmid=17420459}}</ref>  A transplatomic tabacco plant generated through chloroplast mediated transformation was bred with plants that were male sterile with an untouched chloroplast.<ref name=\":03222\" /> The transplastomic plants were engineered to have [[Antimicrobial resistance|resistance]] to the antibiotic [[spectinomycin]] and engineered to produce a [[Green fluorescent protein|fluorescent molecule]] (GFP).<ref name=\":03222\" /> Therefore, it was hypothesized that any offspring produced by from these two lines of tabacco plant should not be able to grow on spectinomycin or be fluorescent, as the genetic material in the chloroplast should not be able to transfer via pollen.<ref name=\":03222\" /> However, it was found that some of the seeds were resistant to the antibiotic and could germinate on spectinomycin agar plates.<ref name=\":03222\" /> Calculations showed that 1 out of every million [[pollen]] grains contained plastid genetic material, which would be hugely significant in an agricultural farm setting.<ref name=\":03222\" /> Because tobacco has a strong tendency towards self-fertilisation, the reliability of transplastomic plants is assumed to be even higher under field conditions. Therefore, the researchers believe that only one in 100,000,000 GM tobacco plants actually would transmit the transgene via pollen. Such values are more than satisfactory to ensure coexistence. However, for GM crops used in the production of pharmaceuticals, or in other cases in which absolutely no outcrossing is permitted, the researchers recommend the combination of chloroplast transformation with other [[biological containment]] methods, such as [[cytoplasmic male sterility]] or transgene mitigation strategies. Therefore what this study showed is that whilst transplatomic plants do not have absolute gene containment, the level of containment is extremely high and would allow for coexistence of conventional and genetically modified agricultural crops.<ref name=\":03222\" />\n\nThere are public concerns about having antibiotic resistant marker genes in the environment, regarding a possible transmission of antibiotic resistant genes to unwanted targets including bacteria and weeds.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Puchta|first=Holger|date=2003-08-01|title=Marker-free transgenic plants|journal=Plant Cell, Tissue and Organ Culture|volume=74|issue=2|pages=123\u2013134|doi=10.1023/A:1023934807184|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref> As a result of this, technologies have been developed to remove the selectable antibiotic resistance gene marker. One such technology that has been implemented is the [[Cre-Lox recombination|Cre/lox system]], where the nuclear encoded Cre recombinase can be placed under control of an [[Promoter (genetics)|inducible promoter]] to remove the antibiotic resistant gene once homoplasmicity has been achieved from the transformation process.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Bala A, Roy A, Das A, Chakraborti D, Das S|date=October 2013|title=Development of selectable marker free, insect resistant, transgenic mustard (Brassica juncea) plants using Cre/lox mediated recombination|journal=BMC Biotechnology|volume=13|issue=1|pages=88|doi=10.1186/1472-6750-13-88|pmc=3819271|pmid=24144281}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.co-extra.eu Co-Extra] Research on the co-existence and traceability of genetically modified plants\n*[http://www.transcontainer.org/UK/ Transcontainer] Developing biological containment systems for genetically modified plants\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Genetically modified organisms in agriculture]]\n", "text_old": "<!--EDIT BELOW THIS LINE-->[[File:Plastids_types_en.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plastids_types_en.svg|thumb|283x283px|Plastid Examples]]\nA '''transplastomic plant''' is a [[genetically modified plant]] in which [[Gene|genes]] are inactivated, modified or new foreign genes are inserted into the [[DNA]] of [[Plastid|plastids]] like the [[chloroplast]] instead of nuclear DNA.\n\nCurrently, the majority of transplastomic plants are as a result of chloroplast manipulation due to poor expression in other [[plastids]].<ref name=\":032\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Rigano MM, Scotti N, Cardi T|date=2012-11-24|title=Unsolved problems in plastid transformation|journal=Bioengineered|volume=3|issue=6|pages=329\u201333|doi=10.4161/bioe.21452|pmc=3489708|pmid=22892591}}</ref>\n\nChloroplasts in plants are thought to have originated from an engulfing event of a photosynthetic bacteria ([[Cyanobacteria|cyanobacterial ancestor)]] by a eukaroyte.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Raven JA, Allen JF|date=2003|title=Genomics and chloroplast evolution: what did cyanobacteria do for plants?|journal=Genome Biology|volume=4|issue=3|pages=209|doi=10.1186/gb-2003-4-3-209|pmc=153454|pmid=12620099}}</ref> There are many advantageous in chloroplast DNA manipulation because of its bacterial origin. For example, the ability to introduce [[Operon|multiple genes]] (operons) in a single step instead of many steps and the simultaneous expression of many genes with its bacterial gene expression system.<ref name=\":23\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Adem M, Beyene D, Feyissa T|date=2017-04-01|title=Recent achievements obtained by chloroplast transformation|journal=Plant Methods|volume=13|issue=1|pages=30|doi=10.1186/s13007-017-0179-1|pmc=5395794|pmid=28428810}}</ref> Other advantageous include, the ability to obtain organic products like [[Protein|proteins]] at a high concentrations and the fact that production of these products will not be affected by [[Epigenetics|epigenetic regulation]].<ref name=\":132\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ahmad N, Michoux F, L\u00f6ssl AG, Nixon PJ|date=November 2016|title=Challenges and perspectives in commercializing plastid transformation technology|url=https://academic.oup.com/jxb/article/67/21/5945/2738940|journal=Journal of Experimental Botany|volume=67|issue=21|pages=5945\u20135960|doi=10.1093/jxb/erw360|pmid=27697788}}</ref> The reason for product synthesis at high concentrations is because a single plant cell can potentially carry up to a 100 chloroplast (like in ''Arabidopsis''), which if all transformed can express the introduced foreign [[Gene|genes)]], compared to transformation of the nucleus which can only express [[Copy-number variation|one copy of the gene]].<ref name=\":032\" />\n\nThe advantageous provided by chloroplast DNA manipulation has seen growing interest into this field of research and development, particularly in agricultural and pharmaceutical applications.<ref name=\":132\" /> However, there are some disadvantageous in chloroplast DNA manipulation, such as the inability to manipulate [[Cereal|cereal crops]] DNA material and poor expression of foreign DNA in non- green plastids as mentioned before.<ref name=\":132\" /> Nevertheless, much progress has been made into plant transplatomics, for example, the production of edible vaccines for [[Tetanus]] by using a transplastomic [[Nicotiana|tobacco]] plant.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Tregoning J, Maliga P, Dougan G, Nixon PJ|date=April 2004|title=New advances in the production of edible plant vaccines: chloroplast expression of a tetanus vaccine antigen, TetC|journal=Phytochemistry|volume=65|issue=8|pages=989\u201394|doi=10.1016/j.phytochem.2004.03.004|pmid=15110679}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n== Transformation and selection procedure ==\n=== Gene construct ===\n[[File:Plant_Gene_Cassette_Schematic_for_Plant_Transplastomics.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plant_Gene_Cassette_Schematic_for_Plant_Transplastomics.jpg|thumb|325x325px|Plant Gene Cassette Schematic for Plant Transplastomics]]\nThe first requirement for transplastomic plant generation is to have a suitable [[Gene cassette|gene construct]] that can be introduced into a plastid like a chloroplast in the form of an ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' [[plasmid]] vector.<ref name=\":0222\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurekaselect.com/72509/article|title=Plant Plastid Engineering|last=Wani|first=Shabir H.|last2=Haider|first2=Nadia|date=2010-10-31|website=Current Genomics|language=en|doi=10.2174/138920210793175912|pmc=PMC3048312|pmid=21532834|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Singh|first3=Hitesh Kumar and N. B.}}</ref> There are several key features of a suitable gene cassette including but not limited to ('''1''') [[selectable marker]] ('''2''') flanking sequences ('''3''') gene of interest ('''4''') [[Promoter (genetics)|promoter sequences]] ('''5''') [[5' UTR]] ('''6''') [[3'-UTR|3' UTR]] ('''7''') [[Intergenic region|intercistronic elements]].<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Verma D, Daniell H|date=December 2007|title=Chloroplast vector systems for biotechnology applications|journal=Plant Physiology|volume=145|issue=4|pages=1129\u201343|doi=10.1104/pp.107.106690|pmc=2151729|pmid=18056863}}</ref> The selectable marker typically tends to be an antiobiotic resistant gene, which would give the plant cell the ability to tolerate being grown on antibiotic containing agar plates.<ref name=\":132\" /> Flanking sequences are crucial for introduction of the gene construct at precised determined points of the plastid genome through [[homologous recombination]].<ref name=\":22222\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Adem M, Beyene D, Feyissa T|date=2017-04-01|title=Recent achievements obtained by chloroplast transformation|journal=Plant Methods|volume=13|issue=1|pages=30|doi=10.1186/s13007-017-0179-1|pmc=5395794|pmid=28428810}}</ref> The gene of interests introduced have many different applications and can range from pest resistance genes to vaccine antigen production.<ref name=\":22222\" /> Intercistronic elements (IEE) are important for facilitating high levels of gene expression if multiple genes are introduced in the form of an [[operon]].<ref name=\":22222\" /> Finally, the 5' UTR and 3' UTR enhances ribosomal binding and increases transcript stability respectively.<ref name=\":22222\" />\n\n=== Transformation and selection ===\nThe most common method for plastid tranformation is [[Gene gun|biolistics]]: Small gold or tungsten particles are coated with the plasmid vector and shot into young plant cells or plant embryos, penetrating multiple cell layers and into the plastid.<ref name=\":0222\" /> There will then be a homologous recombination event between the shot plasmid vector and the [[Genome|plastid's genome]], hopefully resulting in a stable insertion of the gene cassette into the plastid.<ref name=\":0222\" /> Whilst the [[Transformation (genetics)|transformation]] efficiency is lower than in [[Agrobacterium tumefaciens|agrobacterial]] mediated transformation, which is also common in plant genetic engineering, particle bombardment is especially suitable for chloroplast transformation. Other transformation methods include the use of [[polyethylene glycol]] (PEG)- mediated transformation, which involves the removal of the plant [[cell wall]] in order to expose the [[Protoplast|\"naked\" plant cell]] to the foreign genetic material for transformation in the presence of PEG.<ref name=\":0222\" /> PEG- mediated transformation however, is notoriously time consuming, very technical and labor intensive as it requires the removal of the cell wall which is a key protective structural component of the plant cell.<ref name=\":1222\">{{Cite journal|last=Gan|first=Qinhua|last2=Jiang|first2=Jiaoyun|last3=Han|first3=Xiao|last4=Wang|first4=Shifan|last5=Lu|first5=Yandu|date=2018|title=Engineering the Chloroplast Genome of Oleaginous Marine Microalga Nannochloropsis oceanica|url=https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpls.2018.00439/full|journal=Frontiers in Plant Science|language=English|volume=9|doi=10.3389/fpls.2018.00439|issn=1664-462X|pmc=PMC5904192|pmid=29696028}}</ref> Interestingly, a paper released in 2018 has described a successful plastid transformation of the chloroplast from the microalgae species ''[[Nannochloropsis|N. oceanica]]'' and ''[[Chlamydomonas reinhardtii|C. reinhardtii]]'' through [[electroporation]].<ref name=\":1222\" /> Whilst no study has been attempted yet for plastid transformation of [[higher plants]] using electroporation, this could be an interesting area of study for the future.\n\nIn order to persist and be stably maintained in the cell, a plasmid DNA molecule must contain an [[origin of replication]], which allows it to be replicated in the cell independently of the [[chromosome]]. When foreign DNA is first introduced to the plant tissue, not all chloroplasts will have successfully integrated the introduced genetic material.<ref name=\":132\" /> There will be a mixture of normal and transformed chloroplast within the plant cells. This mix of normal and transformed chloroplasts are defined to be \"[[Heteroplasmy|heteroplasmic]]\" chloroplast population.<ref name=\":132\" /> Stable gene expression of the introduced gene requires a \"[[Homoplasmy|homoplasmic]]\" population of transformed chloroplasts in the plant cells, where all the chloroplasts in the plant cell has successfully integrated the foreign genetic material.<ref name=\":132\" /> Typically, homoplasmicity can be achieved and identified through multiple rounds of selection on antibiotics.<ref name=\":132\" /> This is where the transformed plant tissue are grown repeatedly on agar plates that contain antibiotics like spectinomycin.<ref name=\":132\" /> Only plant cells that have successfully integrated the gene cassette as shown above will be able to express the antibiotic resistance selectable marker and therefore grow normally on agar plates containing antibiotics.<ref name=\":132\" /> Plant [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]] that do not grow normally will have a bleached appearance as the spectinomycin antibiotic [[Inhibitor|inhibits]] the [[ribosome]] of the plant cell<ref name=\":132\" /> However, as heteroplasmic population of chloroplasts may still be able to grow on agar plates effectively, many rounds of antibiotic selection and regrowth are required to cultivate a plant tissue that is homoplasmic and stable.<ref name=\":132\" /> Generation of homoplasmic plant tissue is considered to be a major difficulty and incredibly time consuming.<ref name=\":0222\" />\n\n== Biological containment and agricultural coexistence ==\n[[File:Nicotiana Tobacco Plants 1909px.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nicotiana%20Tobacco%20Plants%201909px.jpg|thumb|Nicotiana Tobacco Plant]]\nGenetically modified plants must be safe for the environment and suitable for [[Co-existence of genetically modified and conventional crops and derived food and feed|coexistence with conventional and organic crops]]. A major hurdle for traditional nuclear genetically modified crops is posed by the potential [[outcrossing]] of the [[transgene]] via pollen movement. Initially it was thought that, plastid transformation, which yields transplastomic plants in which the pollen does not contain the transgene, not only increases biosafety, but also facilitates the coexistence of genetically modified, conventional and organic agriculture. Therefore, developing such crops was a major goal of research projects such as [[Co-Extra]] and Transcontainer.\n\nHowever, a study conducted on the [[Nicotiana|tabacco plant]] in 2007 has disproved this theory. Led by Ralph Bock from the Max Planck Institute of Molecular Plant Physiology in Germany, researchers studied genetically modified tobacco in which the transgene was integrated in chloroplasts.<ref name=\":03222\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ruf S, Karcher D, Bock R|date=April 2007|title=Determining the transgene containment level provided by chloroplast transformation|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=104|issue=17|pages=6998\u20137002|doi=10.1073/pnas.0700008104|pmc=1849964|pmid=17420459}}</ref>  A transplatomic tabacco plant generated through chloroplast mediated transformation was bred with plants that were male sterile with an untouched chloroplast.<ref name=\":03222\" /> The transplastomic plants were engineered to have [[Antimicrobial resistance|resistance]] to the antibiotic [[spectinomycin]] and engineered to produce a [[Green fluorescent protein|fluorescent molecule]] (GFP).<ref name=\":03222\" /> Therefore, it was hypothesized that any offspring produced by from these two lines of tabacco plant should not be able to grow on spectinomycin or be fluorescent, as the genetic material in the chloroplast should not be able to transfer via pollen.<ref name=\":03222\" /> However, it was found that some of the seeds were resistant to the antibiotic and could germinate on spectinomycin agar plates.<ref name=\":03222\" /> Calculations showed that 1 out of every million [[pollen]] grains contained plastid genetic material, which would be hugely significant in an agricultural farm setting.<ref name=\":03222\" />Because tobacco has a strong tendency towards self-fertilisation, the reliability of transplastomic plants is assumed to be even higher under field conditions. Therefore, the researchers believe that only one in 100,000,000 GM tobacco plants actually would transmit the transgene via pollen. Such values are more than satisfactory to ensure coexistence. However, for GM crops used in the production of pharmaceuticals, or in other cases in which absolutely no outcrossing is permitted, the researchers recommend the combination of chloroplast transformation with other [[biological containment]] methods, such as [[cytoplasmic male sterility]] or transgene mitigation strategies. Therefore what this study showed is that whilst transplatomic plants do not have absolute gene containment, the level of containment is extremely high and would allow for coexistence of conventional and genetically modified agricultural crops.<ref name=\":03222\" />\n\nThere are public concerns about having antibiotic resistant marker genes in the environment, regarding a possible transmission of antibiotic resistant genes to unwanted targets including bacteria and weeds.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Puchta|first=Holger|date=2003-08-01|title=Marker-free transgenic plants|journal=Plant Cell, Tissue and Organ Culture|volume=74|issue=2|pages=123\u2013134|doi=10.1023/A:1023934807184|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref> As a result of this, technologies have been developed to remove the selectable antibiotic resistance gene marker. One such technology that has been implemented is the [[Cre-Lox recombination|Cre/lox system]], where the nuclear encoded Cre recombinase can be placed under control of an [[Promoter (genetics)|inducible promoter]] to remove the antibiotic resistant gene once homoplasmicity has been achieved from the transformation process.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Bala A, Roy A, Das A, Chakraborti D, Das S|date=October 2013|title=Development of selectable marker free, insect resistant, transgenic mustard (Brassica juncea) plants using Cre/lox mediated recombination|journal=BMC Biotechnology|volume=13|issue=1|pages=88|doi=10.1186/1472-6750-13-88|pmc=3819271|pmid=24144281}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.co-extra.eu Co-Extra] Research on the co-existence and traceability of genetically modified plants\n*[http://www.transcontainer.org/UK/ Transcontainer] Developing biological containment systems for genetically modified plants\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Genetically modified organisms in agriculture]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix PMC warnings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transplastomic_plant"}
{"title_page": "Squares in London", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Sutton Nicholls's view of St. James's Square, c. 1722.jpg|thumb|250px|St. James's Square, c. 1722]]\n[[File:Fitzroy Square from the BT Tower.jpg|thumb|Fitzroy Square]]\n'''Squares''' have long been a feature of '''[[London]]''' and come in numerous identifiable forms. The landscaping spectrum of squares stretches from those containing more [[hardscape]] constituting [[town square]]s (also known as city squares) to those containing planted [[communal gardens]], for which London is a major international exponent, known as [[garden square]]s.  \n\nA few in the capital of the [[United Kingdom]] such as [[Trafalgar Square]] were from the outset ''public'' open spaces in exactly the same way as other city squares worldwide, typically a ''plaza'', ''piazza'' and a ''platz'' in Spain, Italy and Germany. Most, however, were garden squares that were originally built as private communal gardens for use by the inhabitants of the surrounding houses. All types of the space are more prevalent in parts of London with high (urban) density. Some of these gardens are now open to the public, while others, for example around [[Notting Hill]], are railed (a form of fencing) and private.\n\nThe terminology has been loosely applied for over a century.  Some have irregular shape &mdash; three triangles and pentagon feature among those officially named ''Square''. Approbative and technical studies of garden squares commonly cover equivalent landscaped communal gardens not named as a ''Square'' many of which spaces have become small public parks &mdash; a diversity of descriptive names features at [[List of garden squares in London|the list of London's \"garden squares\"]].\n\n==Name and shape==\n\"Square\" is a generic term for neat, planned or set aside urban open spaces larger than a verge or pavement overlooked by buildings. In London elements of fields were set aside, a fact reflected in the name of the square [[London Fields]] and two later examples: [[Coram's Fields]] and [[Lincoln's Inn Fields]].  Some are not actually square, or even rectangular. One reason for this is the use of a local nickname for the street, park or garden in question. Another is that some older squares were irregularly shaped to begin with, or lost their original layout due to the city's many transformations, not least following the [[Great Fire of London]] and [[The Blitz]].\n\nThe street naming (or streetnaming) authority of each [[London Borough]] and the [[City of London Corporation]] by authority of an Act of 1939 imposes rules to authorise appropriate street names for new developments and for owners wishing to rename features.<ref>London Buildings Acts (Amendment) Act 1939, Part 2: Naming and Numbering of Streets and Buildings.</ref>  Commercial building and retained historic names apart, new residential squares must in many boroughs be \"for a square only\" &mdash; considered not well elongated but rectangular and to some extent open.<ref>[https://www.rbkc.gov.uk/sites/default/files/atoms/files/New%20Application%20Pack.pdf Street Naming application pack] Example policy list from Kensington and Chelsea, replacing similar earlier rule. Retrieved 2018-03-12</ref>  Billiter Square, EC3 and Millennium Square, SE1 in districts dominated by retail, commerce and offices are among many modern buildings (not beside a visible rectangular open space) which have alternative, higher built density, square features to their design, such as a courtyard or a square footprint.\n\nSome squares are paved ([[Granary Square]]); some grass and trees ([[Russell Square]]); many others diverse communal gardens. Most of those which are square have the word in their name and these are listed below; others more flexibly identified do not; such notable lists are commonly identified as [[List of garden squares in London|list of garden squares]] or \"estate gardens\", \"communal gardens\", \"formal gardens\" about which many books have been written. Increasingly, spaces are being constructed that are [[Privately owned public space|legally private, although in practice open to the public]] ([[Paternoster Square]]). \n\nThe [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] contains over a hundred garden squares whose use is restricted to residents. The upkeep of these spaces (almost all named after their adjoining streets for example Square/Crescent/Gardens/Place) is partly paid for through a levy on top of residents' [[council tax]].<ref>[http://www.rbkc.gov.uk/gardensquares/general/default.asp \"Your garden square and you\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060711162431/http://www.rbkc.gov.uk/gardensquares/general/default.asp |date=2006-07-11 }}, [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]], London, UK. URL accessed 20 June 2006.</ref> One instance is a [[lens (geometry)|lens]] (pointed oval), [[The Boltons]].\n\nToward the public end of the public/private continuum, London's growth has taken in [[village green]]s. A minority of these partly or wholly survive such as [[Newington Green]] to form council-run open spaces breaking up housing, road networks and/or retail streets. The categories of greens and garden squares become more well-visited scaled up, above an informal cut-off, being the today mainly government-run, characteristic [[parks and open spaces in London]] &mdash; less urban such land includes London's 26 [[list of common land in London|commons]] most of which were significantly reduced in size in the period of [[Inclosure]] and 16 country parks.\n\n==History==\n===Development of Squares===\nThe making of residential squares fell into decline in the early 20th century, one of the last notable such squares having been designed by [[Edwin Lutyens]] for [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]]. Numerous squares were in danger of filling in for further building. This was banned by the [[London Squares Act of 1931]].{{clarify|there is no matching statute listed in the Acts of Parl. of United Kingdom - which Part of which Act does this refer to?|date=March 2018}}<ref name=Phelps>Camilla Phelps, \"London opens its gates\". ''The English Garden'', June 2013, 97.</ref> In the last quarter of the 20th century a fashion for making office squares developed, a trend led by the [[Broadgate]] development. Developers such as London Square, [[Berkeley Homes]] and [[Taylor Wimpey]] (in the first two instances through their London subsidiaries) have built and set aside land in more than one of their 21st century London developments to create those of the residential type.<ref>[http://londonsquare.co.uk/developments/detail/fulham \"Square\"] Details of 21st century square, at Farm Lane, Fulham, London Square Group, 2018</ref><ref>[http://londonsquare.co.uk/developments/detail/teddington \"Square\"\"] Details of 21st century square at Waldegrave Road, Teddington, London Square Group, 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/new-homes/london/orpington/brunswick-square \"Brunswick Square, Orpington\"] Berkeley Homes Group, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.berkeleygroup.co.uk/new-homes/london/kensington/royal-warwick-square \"Royal Warwick Square, Kensington\"], Berkeley Homes Group, 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.taylorwimpey.co.uk/find-your-home/england/london/harrow/st-georges-square \"St George's Square, Sudbury Hill, Harrow\"] Taylor Wimpey, 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.taylorwimpey.co.uk/find-your-home/england/london/surbiton/tolworth-square \"Tolworth Square, Surbiton\"] Taylor Wimpey, 2018</ref> More broadly, [[mixed-use]] squares to give a focal area have become a resurgent planning design, reflected for instance in Times Square, [[Sutton, London|Sutton]] and [[Canada Square]], [[Canary Wharf]].\n\n===Viewings and events in private communal gardens===\n{{See also|List of garden squares in London}}\nSince 1998 many private squares (which term in that context takes in many other shapes of gardens between houses) temporarily open to the paying public: London's \"Open Garden Squares Weekend\", founded by Caroline Aldiss, takes place on the second weekend in June.<ref>Phelps, \"London opens its gates\". ''The English Garden'', June 2013, 95\u201398.</ref> The event is organised by the [[London Parks and Garden Trust]]. In 2013 over 200 gardens took part, including the garden of the [[Prime Minister]] at [[10 Downing Street]] and the Gardens of [[HM Prison Wormwood Scrubs]]. Other events in keynote squares coincide such as a World Archaeology Festival, [[Gordon Square]], Bloomsbury run by [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]].<ref>[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/calendar/articles/20130608 \"World Archaeology Festival 2013\"], UCL.</ref>\n\nThe parks can be categorised as public garden squares, private [[garden square]]s or other squares.\n\n===Social importance===\n[[File:Was that a dream by Cedric Le Borgne.jpg|thumb|An illuminated wire sculpture of a nightingale, displayed in London's [[Berkeley Square]] as part of [[:w:Lumiere festival|Lumiere London 2018]], an art festival. The sculpture and the accompanying soundtrack ''A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square'' formed an art installation titled 'Was that a dream?' by a French artist C\u00e9dric Le Borgne.<ref>{{cite web|title=C\u00e9dric Le Borgne: Was That a Dream?|url=https://www.visitlondon.com/lumiere/installation/46121800-was-that-a-dream#IY6Wbe9wPZIJvO6C.97|website=visitlondon.com|language=en}}</ref>]]\nThe local proliferation relative to other [[United Kingdom|UK]] cities coupled with, since the early 20th century, their widespread opening up has similarly made squares broadly cited in portrayals of London.  Initially cultural use was mainly confined to novels and, to a lesser degree, fine art. \n\n\"[[It's a Long Way to Tipperary]]\" is a 1910s song featuring the line \"Farewell [[Leicester Square]]\". \"[[A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square]]\" is a romantic [[popular song|hit]] of 1940 with lyrics by [[Eric Maschwitz]] and music by [[Manning Sherwin]], sang that year separately by [[Ray Noble (musician)|Ray Noble]] and [[Vera Lynn]] and a theme of a film the next year, by [[Fritz Lang]]., ''[[Man Hunt (1941 film)|Man Hunt]]''.  In the 1956 song \"Why Can't The English?\" from the musical ''[[My Fair Lady]]'', Professor Henry Higgins laments, \"Hear them down in Soho Square/Dropping H's everywhere.\"\n\nDrama most notably includes the high-audience [[soap opera]] broadcast by the [[BBC]] running since 1985, ''[[EastEnders]]'' based on a semi-permanent set north of London's border, [[Albert Square]]. It had pre-release titles ''Square Dance, Round the Square, Round the Houses, London Pride'' and ''East 8''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Rupert|title=EastEnders: 20 Years in Albert Square|publisher=BBC Books|year=2005|isbn=978-0-563-52165-5|format=Hardback|page=15}}</ref>\n\n[[Soho Square]] garden contains a bench that commemorates the singer [[Kirsty MacColl]], who wrote the song \"Soho Square\" for her album ''[[Titanic Days]]''. After her death in 2000, fans bought a memorial bench in her honour, inscribing the lyrics: \"One day I'll be waiting there / No empty bench in Soho Square\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kirstymaccoll.com/information/memorial/bench/index.htm |title=Bench in Soho Square |publisher=Kirsty MacColl |date=2001-08-12 |accessdate=2011-02-03}}</ref> The [[Lindisfarne (band)|Lindisfarne]] album ''Elvis Lives On the Moon'' also includes a song named after that square.<ref>http://www.lindisfarne.co.uk/discography/elvis-lives-on-the-moon.htm</ref>\n\n==Notable communal gardens surrounded by buildings==\n{{main|List of garden squares in London}}\n*[[Arundel Gardens]]\n*[[Park Crescent, London|Park Crescent]]\n*[[Royal Crescent, London|Royal Crescent]]\n*[[Cambridge Gardens, London]]\n*[[Egerton Gardens]]\n*[[Finsbury Circus]]\n*[[Grosvenor Square]]\n*[[Hans Place]]\n*[[Lennox Gardens, London]]\n*[[Russell Square]]\n*[[Belgrave Square]]\n*[[Berkeley Square]]\n*[[Kensington Square]]\n*[[Kensington Park Gardens]]\n*[[Golden Square]]\n*[[Soho Square]]\n*[[Bedford Square]]\n*[[Sloane Square]]\n*[[St. James's Square]]\n*[[Clapton Square]]\n*[[St George's Square]]\n*[[Harrington Gardens]]\n*[[The Boltons]]\n*[[Wilton Crescent]]\n\n==Most notable town squares==\n*[[Trafalgar Square]]\n*[[Leicester Square]]\n*[[Parliament Square]]\n\n==List of Greater London squares==\n{{Expand list|date=March 2018}}\n\nIt comprises roads and notable other places bearing the word ''Square''. The tables state if each has an open-air public part; those marked ''No'' may be squares in an unconventional sense or relic (a throwback) to what stood on their site before.\n\nDemolished squares are listed in a table at the end of this section.\n\nArea includes hardscapes and roads within.  They are arranged by postcode, see the map below of postcodes.\n[[File:LONDON post town map.svg|thumb|London post town postcodes]]\n===Centremost postcodes===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name!!Post district!!Open-to-sky area between buildings!!Image!!m\u00b2\n|-\n|King||EC1||Mainly||[[File:King Square Gardens Borough of Islington London August 11th 2014 - 05.jpg|80px]]||16000\n|-\n|[[Charterhouse Square|Charterhouse]]||EC1||Yes||[[File:Charterhouse Square.jpg|80px]]{{refn|group=n|A pentagon.  One actual square is directly north and commonly confused by map makers, the Green. Nine courtyards which are smaller exist e.g. Preacher's Court, Pensioners Court, Masters Court: mostly green.}}<ref>{{NHLE|num=1206699|desc=lamp post in Pensioners Court}}</ref>\n||9300\n|-\n|Northampton||EC1||Yes||[[File:Northampton Square - geograph.org.uk - 979.jpg|80px]]||6600\n|-\n|Brewery||EC1||Yes||[[File:Brewery Square, Clerkenwell EC1V small.png|80px]]||900\n|-\n|Waterhouse||EC1||Yes||[[File:Holborn, Waterhouse Square, 142 Holborn Bars, EC1 - geograph.org.uk - 667992.jpg|80px]]{{refn|group=n|By subdivision of a building (into three) still a courtyard but linked by public ways to all but north side, formerly Furni